1
00:00:30,880 --> 00:00:37,840
Patrol Cruiser "IP-T 247" circling out 
toward Pluto on leisurely inspection tour  

2
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:42,880
to visit the outpost miners there, was 
in no hurry at all as she loafed along.  

3
00:00:43,760 --> 00:00:49,760
Her six-man crew was taking it very easy, and 
easy meant two-man watches, and low speed,  

4
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:53,200
to watch for the instrument panel 
and attend ship into the bargain.

5
00:00:54,320 --> 00:00:59,120
She was about thirty million miles off Pluto, 
just beginning to get in touch with some of the  

6
00:00:59,120 --> 00:01:04,960
larger mining stations out there, when Buck 
Kendall's turn at the controls came along.  

7
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:12,800
Buck Kendall was one of life's little jokes. 
When Nature made him, she was absentminded.  

8
00:01:13,680 --> 00:01:19,520
Buck stood six feet two in his stocking feet, 
with his usual slight stoop in operation.  

9
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:23,920
When he forgot, and stood up straight, 
he loomed about two inches higher.  

10
00:01:25,120 --> 00:01:29,840
He had the body and muscles of a dock 
navvy, which Nature started out to make.  

11
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:35,360
Then she forgot and added something of the 
same stuff she put in Sir Francis Drake.  

12
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:42,640
Maybe that made Old Nature nervous, and she 
started adding different things. At any rate,  

13
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:48,880
Kendall, as finally turned out, had a brain that 
put him in the first rank of scientists—when  

14
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:54,240
he felt like it—the general constitution 
of an ostrich and a flair for gambling.

15
00:01:55,280 --> 00:02:02,480
The present position was due to such a gamble. An 
IP man, a friend of his, had made the mistake of  

16
00:02:02,480 --> 00:02:09,040
betting him a thousand dollars he wouldn't get 
beyond a Captain's bars in the Patrol. Kendall  

17
00:02:09,040 --> 00:02:15,680
had liked the idea anyway, and adding a bit of 
a bet to it made it irresistible. So, being a  

18
00:02:15,680 --> 00:02:22,800
very particular kind of a fool, the glorious kind 
which old Nature turns out now and then, he left a  

19
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:28,880
five million dollar estate on Long Island, Terra, 
that same evening, and joined up in the Patrol.  

20
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:36,560
The Sir Francis Drake strain had immediately come 
forth—and Kendall was having the time of his life.  

21
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:44,800
In a six-man cruiser, his real work in the 
Interplanetary Patrol had started. He was still in  

22
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:51,040
it—but it was his command now, and a blue circle 
on his left sleeve gave his lieutenant's rank.

23
00:02:52,160 --> 00:02:56,640
Buck Kendall had immediately proceeded 
to enlist in his command the IP man  

24
00:02:56,640 --> 00:03:01,680
who had made the mistaken bet, and 
Rad Cole was on duty with him now.  

25
00:03:02,720 --> 00:03:10,080
Cole was the technician of the T-247. His 
rank as Technical Engineer was practically  

26
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:14,320
equivalent to Kendall's circle-rank, which 
made the two more comfortable together.

27
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:19,600
Cole was listening carefully to the 
signals coming through from Pluto.  

28
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:26,000
"That," he decided, "sounds like Tad 
Nichols' fist. You can recognize that  

29
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,720
broken-down truck-horse trot of his on 
the key as far away as you can hear it."

30
00:03:31,440 --> 00:03:37,920
"Is that what it is?" sighed Buck. "I thought it 
was static mushing him at first. What's he like?"

31
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:44,880
"Like all the other damn fools who come out two 
billion miles to scratch rock, as if there weren't  

32
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:51,200
enough already on the inner planets. He's got a 
rich platinum property. Sells ninety percent of  

33
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:55,920
his output to buy his power, and the other 
eleven percent for his clothes and food."

34
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:02,720
"He must be an efficient miner," suggested 
Kendall, "to maintain 101% production like that."

35
00:04:03,760 --> 00:04:09,680
"No, but his bank account is. He's figured out 
that's the most economic level of production.  

36
00:04:10,320 --> 00:04:15,680
If he produces less, he won't be able to pay 
for his heating power, and if he produces more,  

37
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:19,200
his operation power will burn 
up his bank account too fast."

38
00:04:20,720 --> 00:04:24,880
"Hmmm—sensible way to figure. 
A man after my own heart.  

39
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:27,840
How does he plan to restock his bank account?"

40
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:36,160
"By mining on Mercury. He does it regularly—sort 
of a commuter. Out here his power bills eat it up.  

41
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:41,840
On Mercury he goes in for potassium, and sells the 
power he collects in cooling his dome, of course.  

42
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:45,680
He's a good miner, and the old 
fool can make money down there."  

43
00:04:46,960 --> 00:04:51,760
Like any really skilled operator, Cole 
had been sending Morse messages while  

44
00:04:51,760 --> 00:04:56,960
he talked. Now he sat quiet waiting for 
the reply, glancing at the chronometer.

45
00:04:59,760 --> 00:05:03,920
"I take it he's not after money—just 
after fun," suggested Buck.

46
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:10,240
"Oh, no. He's after money," replied Cole 
gravely. "You ask him—he's going to make  

47
00:05:10,240 --> 00:05:16,160
his eternal fortune yet by striking a real 
bed of jovium, and then he'll retire."

48
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:18,880
"Oh, one of that kind."

49
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:24,640
"They all are," Cole laughed. 
"Eternal hope, and the rest of it."  

50
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:32,080
He listened a moment and went on. "But old Nichols 
is a first-grade engineer. He wouldn't be able  

51
00:05:32,080 --> 00:05:39,440
to remake that bankroll every time if he wasn't. 
You'll see his Dome out there on Pluto—it's always  

52
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:47,360
the best on the planet. Tip-top shape. And he's 
a bit of an experimenter too. Ah—he's with us."

53
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:53,760
Nichols' ragged signals were coming through—or 
pounding through. They were worse than usual,  

54
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:56,160
and at first Kendall and 
Cole couldn't make them out.  

55
00:05:56,960 --> 00:06:02,880
Then finally they got them in bursts. The man 
was excited, and his bad key-work made it worse.  

56
00:06:04,480 --> 00:06:10,960
"—Randing stopped. They got him I 
think. He said—th—ship as big—a—nsport.  

57
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:23,920
Said it wa—eaded my—ay. Neutrons—on 
instruments—he's coming over the horizon—it's  

58
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:35,360
huge—war ship I think—register—instru—neutrons—." 
Abruptly the signals were blanked out completely.

59
00:06:37,280 --> 00:06:44,720
Cole and Kendall sat frozen and stiff. Each 
looked at the other abruptly, then Kendall moved.  

60
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:50,000
From the receiver, he ripped out the recording 
coil, and instantly jammed it into the analyzer.  

61
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:56,160
He started it through once, then again, then 
again, at different tone settings, till he found  

62
00:06:56,160 --> 00:07:05,200
a very shrill whine that seemed to clear up most 
of Nichols' bad key-work. "T-247—T-247—Emergency.  

63
00:07:05,760 --> 00:07:15,840
Emergency. Randing reports the—over 
his horizon. Huge—ip—reign manufacture.  

64
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:23,600
Almost spherical. Randing's stopped. They 
got him I think. He said the ship was as  

65
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:28,368
big as a transport. Said it was headed 
my way. Neutrons—ont—gister—instruments.  

66
00:07:32,400 --> 00:07:35,760
I think—is h—he's coming over the horizon.  

67
00:07:36,480 --> 00:07:40,560
It's huge, and a war ship I 
think—register—instruments—neutrons."

68
00:07:43,600 --> 00:07:48,240
Kendall's finger stabbed out at a button. 
Instantly the noise of the other men,  

69
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:53,680
wakened abruptly by the mild shocks, came 
from behind. Kendall swung to the controls,  

70
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:59,520
and Cole raced back to the engine room. The 
hundred-foot ship shot suddenly forward under  

71
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:06,080
the thrust of her tail ion-rockets. A blue-red 
cloud formed slowly behind her and expanded.  

72
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:13,200
Talbot appeared, and silently took her over 
from Kendall. "Stations, men," snapped Kendall.  

73
00:08:13,920 --> 00:08:18,720
"Emergency call from a miner of Pluto reporting 
a large armed vessel which attacked them."  

74
00:08:19,760 --> 00:08:24,800
Kendall swung back, and eased himself against the 
thrusting acceleration of the over-powered little  

75
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:31,280
ship, toward the engine room. Cole was bending 
over his apparatus, making careful check-ups,  

76
00:08:31,280 --> 00:08:38,400
closing weapon-circuits. No window gave view of 
space here; on the left was the tiny tender's  

77
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:43,600
pocket, on the right, above and below the 
great water tanks that fed the ion-rockets,  

78
00:08:43,600 --> 00:08:49,840
behind the rockets themselves. The tungsten metal 
walls were cold and gray under the ship lights;  

79
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:57,360
the hunched bulks of the apparatus crowded the 
tiny room. Gigantic racked accumulators huddled  

80
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:02,880
in the corners. Martin and Garnet swung into 
position in the fighting-tanks just ahead of  

81
00:09:02,880 --> 00:09:09,280
the power rooms; Canning slid rapidly through 
the engine room, oozed through a tiny door,  

82
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:14,560
and took up his position in the stern-chamber, 
seated half-over the great ion-rocket sheath.

83
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:18,160
"Ready in positions, Captain Kendall," called the  

84
00:09:18,160 --> 00:09:22,000
war-pilot as the little green 
lights appeared on his board.

85
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:28,320
"Test discharges on maximum," ordered Kendall. 
He turned to Cole. "You start the automatic key?"

86
00:09:29,280 --> 00:09:29,920
"Right, Captain."

87
00:09:30,800 --> 00:09:31,520
"All shipshape?"

88
00:09:32,240 --> 00:09:38,000
"Right as can be. Accumulators at thirty-seven 
per cent, thanks to the loaf out here. They ought  

89
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:43,200
to pick up our signal back on Jupiter, he's 
nearest now. The station on Europa will get it."

90
00:09:44,160 --> 00:09:49,840
"Talbot—we are only to investigate if the ship 
is as reported. Have you seen any signs of her?"

91
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:52,480
"No sir, and the signals are blank."

92
00:09:53,680 --> 00:09:59,840
"I'll work from here." Kendall took his position 
at the commanding control. Cole made way for him,  

93
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:05,200
and moved to the power board. One by one he tested 
the automatic doors, the pressure bulkheads.  

94
00:10:06,560 --> 00:10:10,320
Kendall watched the instruments as one 
after another of the weapons were tested  

95
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:15,920
on momentary full discharge—titanic 
flames of five million volt protons.  

96
00:10:16,560 --> 00:10:19,600
Then the ship thudded to the 
chatter of the Garnell rifles.

97
00:10:20,480 --> 00:10:24,720
Tensely the men watched the planet 
ahead, white, yet barely visible in  

98
00:10:24,720 --> 00:10:31,920
the weak sunlight so far out. It was swimming 
slowly nearer as the tiny ship gathered speed.

99
00:10:31,920 --> 00:10:34,720
Kendall cast a glance over 
his detector-instruments.  

100
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:40,720
The radio network was undisturbed, the 
magnetic and electric fields recognized  

101
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:46,720
only the slight disturbances occasioned by 
the planet itself. There was nothing, noth—

102
00:10:47,840 --> 00:10:54,240
Five hundred miles away, a gigantic 
ship came into instantaneous being.  

103
00:10:55,760 --> 00:11:02,960
Simultaneously, and instantaneously, the various 
detector systems howled their warnings. Kendall  

104
00:11:02,960 --> 00:11:08,160
gasped as the thing appeared on his view 
screen, with the scale-lines below. The scale  

105
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:14,880
must be cock-eyed. They said the ship was fifteen 
hundred feet in diameter, and two thousand long!

106
00:11:16,080 --> 00:11:19,520
"Retreat," ordered Kendall, 
"at maximum acceleration."

107
00:11:20,800 --> 00:11:26,720
Talbot was already acting. The gyroscopes hummed 
in their castings, and the motors creaked.  

108
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:33,840
The T-247 spun on her axis, and abruptly the 
acceleration built up as the ion-rockets began  

109
00:11:33,840 --> 00:11:38,720
to shudder. A faint smell of "heat" 
began to creep out of the converter.  

110
00:11:39,520 --> 00:11:43,680
Immense "weight" built up, and pressed the 
men into their specially designed seats—

111
00:11:44,560 --> 00:11:53,120
The gigantic ship across the way turned slowly, 
and seemed to stare at the T-247. Then it darted  

112
00:11:53,120 --> 00:11:59,520
toward them at incredible speed till the poor 
little T-247 seemed to be standing still,  

113
00:11:59,520 --> 00:12:06,000
as sailors say. The stranger was so gigantic 
now, the screens could not show all of him.

114
00:12:07,440 --> 00:12:09,840
"God, Buck—he's going to take us!"

115
00:12:10,720 --> 00:12:17,840
Simultaneously, the T-247 rolled, and from her 
broke every possible stream of destruction.  

116
00:12:18,400 --> 00:12:24,720
The ion-rocket flames swirled abruptly toward 
her, the proton-guns whined their song of death  

117
00:12:24,720 --> 00:12:29,440
in their housings, and the heavy pounding 
shudder of the Garnell guns racked the ship.

118
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:34,720
Strangely, Kendall suddenly noticed, 
there was a stillness in the ship.  

119
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:41,120
The guns and the rays were still going—but 
the little human sounds seemed abruptly gone.

120
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:46,640
"Talbot—Garnet—" Only silence answered him.  

121
00:12:47,520 --> 00:12:51,840
Cole looked across at him in 
sudden white-faced amazement.

122
00:12:52,400 --> 00:12:54,720
"They're gone—" gasped Cole.

123
00:12:56,160 --> 00:13:01,120
Kendall stood paralyzed for thirty seconds. 
Then suddenly he seemed to come to life.  

124
00:13:02,480 --> 00:13:06,640
"Neutrons! Neutrons—and water 
tanks! Old Nichols was right—"  

125
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:14,640
He turned to his friend. "Cole—the tender—quick." 
He darted a glance at the screen. The giant  

126
00:13:14,640 --> 00:13:21,680
ship still lay alongside. A wash of ions was 
curling around her, splitting, and passing on.  

127
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:27,920
The pinprick explosions of the Garnell shells 
dotted space around her—but never on her.

128
00:13:29,200 --> 00:13:34,800
Cole was already racing for the tender lock. 
In an instant Kendall piled in after him.  

129
00:13:35,760 --> 00:13:41,600
The tiny ship, scarcely ten feet long, was powered 
for flights of only two hours acceleration,  

130
00:13:41,600 --> 00:13:47,200
and had oxygen for but twenty-four hours for 
six men, seventy-two hours for two men—maybe.  

131
00:13:48,720 --> 00:13:52,640
The heavy door was slammed shut behind 
them, as Cole seated himself at the  

132
00:13:52,640 --> 00:13:59,600
panel. He depressed a lever, and a sudden 
smooth push shot them away from the T-247.

133
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:05,920
"DON'T!" called Kendall sharply as Cole 
reached for the ion-rocket control.  

134
00:14:06,640 --> 00:14:15,200
"Douse those lights!" The ship was dark in dark 
space. The lighted hull of the T-247 drifted away  

135
00:14:15,200 --> 00:14:20,880
from the little tender—further and further till 
the giant ship on the far side became visible.

136
00:14:22,080 --> 00:14:28,320
"Not a light—not a sign of fields in operation." 
Kendall said, unconsciously speaking softly.  

137
00:14:29,200 --> 00:14:32,320
"This thing is so tiny, that it 
may escape their observation in  

138
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:36,560
the fields of the T-247 and Pluto 
down there. It's our only hope."

139
00:14:38,080 --> 00:14:42,800
"What happened? How in the name of the 
planets did they kill those men without a  

140
00:14:42,800 --> 00:14:47,120
sound, without a flash, and without 
even warning us, or injuring us?"

141
00:14:48,240 --> 00:14:49,760
"Neutrons—don't you see?"

142
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:54,800
"Frankly, I don't. I'm no 
scientist—merely a technician.  

143
00:14:55,760 --> 00:14:58,560
Neutrons aren't used in any 
process I've run across."

144
00:15:00,080 --> 00:15:07,120
"Well, remember they're uncharged, tiny things. 
Small as protons, but without electric field. The  

145
00:15:07,120 --> 00:15:12,320
result is they pass right through an ordinary atom 
without being stopped unless they make a direct  

146
00:15:12,320 --> 00:15:19,520
hit. Tungsten, while it has a beautifully high 
melting point, is mostly open space, and a neutron  

147
00:15:19,520 --> 00:15:25,760
just sails right through it, or any heavy atom. 
Light atoms stop neutrons better—there's less open  

148
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:33,760
space in 'em. Hydrogen is best. Well—a man is made 
up mostly of light elements, and a man stops those  

149
00:15:33,760 --> 00:15:39,840
neutrons—it isn't surprising it killed those 
other fellows invisibly, and without a sound."

150
00:15:41,120 --> 00:15:43,600
"You mean they bathed that ship in neutrons?"

151
00:15:44,640 --> 00:15:48,880
"Shot it full of 'em. Just like our 
proton guns, only sending neutrons."

152
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:52,000
"Well, why weren't we killed too?"

153
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:56,880
"'Water stops neutrons,' I said. Figure it out."

154
00:15:58,480 --> 00:16:06,240
"The rocket-water tanks—all around us! Great 
masses of water—" gasped Cole. "That saved us?"

155
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:09,600
"Right. I wonder if they've spotted us."

156
00:16:11,040 --> 00:16:15,280
The stranger ship was moving 
slowly in relation to the T-247.  

157
00:16:16,080 --> 00:16:22,720
Suddenly the motion changed, the stranger spun—and 
a giant lock appeared in her side, opened.  

158
00:16:23,600 --> 00:16:29,760
The T-247 began to move, floated more 
and more rapidly straight for the lock.  

159
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:36,320
Her various weapons had stopped operating now, 
the hoppers of the Garnell guns exhausted,  

160
00:16:36,320 --> 00:16:41,280
the charge of the accumulators aboard the 
ship down so low the proton guns had died out.

161
00:16:42,720 --> 00:16:44,800
"Lord—they're taking the whole ship!"

162
00:16:46,080 --> 00:16:52,560
"Say—Cole, is that any ship you ever heard of 
before? I don't think that's just a pirate!"

163
00:16:53,920 --> 00:16:55,520
"Not a pirate—what then?"

164
00:16:56,160 --> 00:17:02,400
"How'd he get inside our detector screens so 
fast? Watch—he'll either leave, or come after us—"  

165
00:17:03,520 --> 00:17:10,080
The T-247 had settled inside the lock now, 
and the great metal door closed after it.  

166
00:17:10,880 --> 00:17:17,760
The whole patrol ship had been swallowed 
by a giant. Kendall was sketching swiftly  

167
00:17:17,760 --> 00:17:23,680
on a notebook, watching the vast ship closely, 
putting down a record of its lines, and formation.  

168
00:17:24,560 --> 00:17:28,480
He glanced up at it, and then down 
for a few more lines, and up at it—

169
00:17:29,520 --> 00:17:36,560
The stranger ship abruptly dwindled. It dwindled 
with incredible speed, rushing off along the line  

170
00:17:36,560 --> 00:17:42,400
of sight at an impossible velocity, and abruptly 
clicking out of sight, like an image on a  

171
00:17:42,400 --> 00:17:47,840
movie-film that has been cut, and repaired after 
the scene that showed the final disappearance.

172
00:17:49,120 --> 00:17:52,960
"Cole—Cole—did you get that? Did you see—do  

173
00:17:53,680 --> 00:17:58,640
you understand what happened?" 
Kendall was excitedly shouting now.

174
00:17:59,680 --> 00:18:04,560
"He missed us," Cole sighed. "It's 
a wonder—hanging out here in space,  

175
00:18:04,560 --> 00:18:07,520
with the protector of the T-247's fields gone."

176
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:15,040
"No, no, you asteroid—that's not it. 
He went off faster than light itself!"

177
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:20,640
"Eh—what? Faster than light? That can't be done—"

178
00:18:21,840 --> 00:18:29,200
"He did it, I know he did. That's how he got 
inside our screens. He came inside faster  

179
00:18:29,200 --> 00:18:34,320
than the warning message could relay back the 
information. Didn't you see him accelerate to  

180
00:18:34,320 --> 00:18:40,960
an impossible speed in an impossible time? Didn't 
you see how he just vanished as he exceeded the  

181
00:18:40,960 --> 00:18:47,600
speed of light, and stopped reflecting it? 
That ship was no ship of this solar system!"

182
00:18:48,720 --> 00:18:50,000
"Where did he come from then?"

183
00:18:51,360 --> 00:18:55,840
"God only knows, but it's a long, long way off."

184
00:19:04,880 --> 00:19:18,960
The IP-M-122 picked them up.  

185
00:19:20,240 --> 00:19:26,880
The M-122 got out there two days later, in 
response to the calls the T-247 had sent out.  

186
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:33,040
As soon as she got within ten million miles of the 
little tender, she began getting Cole's signals,  

187
00:19:33,040 --> 00:19:37,840
and within twelve hours had reached the 
tiny thing, located it, and picked it up.

188
00:19:38,400 --> 00:19:43,040
Captain Jim Warren was in command, one 
of the old school commanders of the IP.  

189
00:19:44,320 --> 00:19:50,560
He listened to Kendall's report, listened to 
Cole's tale—and radioed back a report of his own.  

190
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:58,400
Space pirates in a large ship had attacked the 
T-247, he said, and carried it away. He advised  

191
00:19:58,400 --> 00:20:04,320
a close watch. On Pluto, his investigations 
disclosed nothing more than the fact that three  

192
00:20:04,320 --> 00:20:09,760
mines had been raided, all platinum supplies 
taken, and the records and machinery removed.

193
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:18,160
The M-122 was a fifty-man patrol cruiser, and 
Warren felt sure he could handle the menace alone,  

194
00:20:18,160 --> 00:20:22,480
and hung around for over two weeks 
looking for it. He saw nothing,  

195
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:29,280
and no further reports came of attack. Again and 
again, Kendall tried to convince him this ship he  

196
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:35,920
was hunting was no mere space pirate, and again 
and again Warren grunted, and went on his way.  

197
00:20:37,040 --> 00:20:43,280
He would not send in any report Kendall made out, 
because to do so would add his endorsement to  

198
00:20:43,280 --> 00:20:48,480
that report. He would not take Kendall back, 
though that was well within his authority.

199
00:20:49,920 --> 00:20:56,080
In fact, it was a full month before Kendall again 
set foot on any of the Minor Planets, and then it  

200
00:20:56,080 --> 00:21:03,280
was Mars, the base of the M-122. Kendall and Cole 
took passage immediately on an IP supply ship,  

201
00:21:03,280 --> 00:21:09,360
and landed in New York six days later. At once, 
Kendall headed for Commander McLaurin's office.  

202
00:21:10,240 --> 00:21:14,400
Buck Kendall, lieutenant of the 
IP, found he would have to make  

203
00:21:14,400 --> 00:21:18,640
regular application to see McLaurin 
through a dozen intermediate officers.

204
00:21:20,560 --> 00:21:26,080
By this time, Kendall was savagely determined 
to see McLaurin himself, and see him in the  

205
00:21:26,080 --> 00:21:32,320
least possible time. Cole, too, was beginning to 
believe in Kendall's assertion of the stranger  

206
00:21:32,320 --> 00:21:39,760
ship's extra-systemic origin. As yet neither could 
understand the strange actions of the machine,  

207
00:21:39,760 --> 00:21:43,840
its attack on the Pluto mines, and the 
capture and theft of a patrol ship.

208
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:53,440
"There is," said Kendall angrily, "just one way 
to see McLaurin and see him quick. And, by God,  

209
00:21:53,440 --> 00:21:59,760
I'm going to. Will you resign with me, Cole? 
I'll see him within a week then, I'll bet."

210
00:22:00,960 --> 00:22:08,960
For a minute, Cole hesitated. Then he shook hands 
with his friends. "Today!" And that day it was.  

211
00:22:09,680 --> 00:22:16,000
They resigned, together. Immediately, Buck Kendall 
got the machinery in motion for an interview,  

212
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:20,640
working now from the outside, pulling the 
strings with the weight of a hundred million  

213
00:22:20,640 --> 00:22:26,960
dollar fortune. Even the IP officers had to 
pay a bit of attention when Bernard Kendall,  

214
00:22:26,960 --> 00:22:34,720
multi-millionaire began talking and demanding 
things. Within a week, Kendall did see McLaurin.

215
00:22:36,560 --> 00:22:42,800
At that time, McLaurin was fifty-three years 
old, his crisp hair still black as space, with  

216
00:22:42,800 --> 00:22:48,560
scarcely a touch of the gray that appears in his 
more recent photographs. He stood six feet tall,  

217
00:22:48,560 --> 00:22:53,840
a broad-shouldered, powerful man, his face 
grave with lines of intelligence and character.  

218
00:22:54,960 --> 00:23:00,560
There was also a permanent narrowing of the 
eyes, from years under the blazing sun of space.  

219
00:23:01,280 --> 00:23:07,920
But most of all, while those years in space had 
narrowed and set his eyes, they had not narrowed  

220
00:23:07,920 --> 00:23:14,960
and set his mind. An infinitely finer character 
than old Jim Warren, his experience in space had  

221
00:23:14,960 --> 00:23:21,280
taught him always to expect the unexpected, to 
understand the incomprehensible as being part  

222
00:23:21,280 --> 00:23:26,720
of the unknown and incalculable properties 
of space and the worlds that swam in it.  

223
00:23:27,680 --> 00:23:33,520
Besides the fine technical education he had 
started with, he had acquired a liberal education  

224
00:23:33,520 --> 00:23:39,200
in mankind. When Buck Kendall, straight and 
powerful, came into his office with Cole,  

225
00:23:39,840 --> 00:23:44,560
he recognized in him a character that would 
drive steadily and straight for its goal.  

226
00:23:45,680 --> 00:23:51,520
Also, he recognized behind the millionaire that 
had succeeded in pulling wires enough to see him,  

227
00:23:51,520 --> 00:23:56,240
the scientist who had had more than one 
paper published "in an amateur way."

228
00:23:58,240 --> 00:24:00,640
"Dr. Bernard Kendall?" he asked, rising.

229
00:24:01,600 --> 00:24:04,000
"Yes, sir. Late Buck Kendall, lieutenant  

230
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:08,400
of the IP. I quit and got Cole here 
to quit with me, so we could see you."

231
00:24:09,840 --> 00:24:15,600
"Unusual tactics. I've had several men join up 
to get an interview with me." McLaurin smiled.

232
00:24:16,800 --> 00:24:23,280
"Yes, I can imagine that, but we had to see 
you in a hurry. A hidebound old rapscallion  

233
00:24:23,280 --> 00:24:28,800
by the name of Jim Warren picked us up out by 
Pluto, floating around in a six-man tender.  

234
00:24:29,680 --> 00:24:34,320
We made some reports to him, but he wouldn't 
believe, and he wouldn't send them through—so we  

235
00:24:34,320 --> 00:24:42,240
had to send ourselves through. Sir, this system is 
about to be attacked by some extra-systemic race.  

236
00:24:42,800 --> 00:24:49,120
The IP-T-247 was so attacked, her crew killed 
off, and the ship itself carried away."

237
00:24:49,840 --> 00:24:52,960
"I got the report Captain Jim Warren sent through,  

238
00:24:52,960 --> 00:24:57,200
stating it was a gang of space pirates. 
Now what makes you believe otherwise?"

239
00:24:58,640 --> 00:25:02,400
"That ship that attacked us, 
attacked with a neutron gun,  

240
00:25:03,120 --> 00:25:09,600
a gun that shot neutrons through the hull of our 
ship as easily as protons pass through open space.  

241
00:25:10,400 --> 00:25:15,520
Those neutrons killed off four of the crew, 
and spared us only because we happened to be  

242
00:25:15,520 --> 00:25:22,000
behind the water tanks. Masses of hydrogen will 
stop neutrons, so we lived, and escaped in the  

243
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:28,160
tender. The little tender, lightless, escaped 
their observation, and we were picked up.  

244
00:25:28,160 --> 00:25:35,600
Now, when the 247 had been picked up, and locked 
into their ship, that ship started accelerating.  

245
00:25:35,600 --> 00:25:40,320
It accelerated so fast along my line of 
sight that it just dwindled, and—vanished.  

246
00:25:41,440 --> 00:25:46,320
It didn't vanish in distance, it vanished 
because it exceeded the speed of light."

247
00:25:47,840 --> 00:25:49,120
"Isn't that impossible?"

248
00:25:50,160 --> 00:25:55,840
"Not at all. It can be done—if you can find 
some way of escaping from this space to do it.  

249
00:25:56,880 --> 00:26:01,440
Now if you could cut across through a higher 
dimension, your projection in this dimension  

250
00:26:01,440 --> 00:26:06,880
might easily exceed the speed of light. For 
instance, if I could cut directly through  

251
00:26:06,880 --> 00:26:11,680
the Earth, at a speed of one thousand miles 
an hour, my projection on the surface would  

252
00:26:11,680 --> 00:26:17,360
go twelve thousand miles while I was going 
eight. Similar, if you could cut through the  

253
00:26:17,360 --> 00:26:22,000
four dimensional space instead of following its 
surface, you'd attain a speed greater than light."

254
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:28,160
"Might it not still be a space pirate? 
That's a lot easier to believe,  

255
00:26:28,160 --> 00:26:31,200
even allowing your statement that 
he exceeded the speed of light."

256
00:26:32,880 --> 00:26:37,680
"If you invented a neutron gun which could 
kill through tungsten walls without injuring  

257
00:26:37,680 --> 00:26:43,920
anything within, a system of accelerating a ship 
that didn't affect the inhabitants of that ship,  

258
00:26:43,920 --> 00:26:47,920
and a means of exceeding the speed of light, 
all within a few months of each other,  

259
00:26:48,480 --> 00:26:54,640
would you become a pirate? I wouldn't, and I 
don't think any one else would. A pirate is a  

260
00:26:54,640 --> 00:27:00,000
man who seeks adventure and relief from work. 
Given a means of exceeding the speed of light,  

261
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:05,840
I'd get all the adventure I wanted investigating 
other planets. If I didn't have a cent before,  

262
00:27:06,560 --> 00:27:11,920
I'd have relief from work by selling it for 
a few hundred millions—and I'd sell it mighty  

263
00:27:11,920 --> 00:27:18,240
easily too, for an invention like that is 
worth an incalculable sum. Tie to that the  

264
00:27:18,240 --> 00:27:24,640
value of compensated acceleration, and no man's 
going to turn pirate. He can make more millions  

265
00:27:24,640 --> 00:27:29,840
selling his inventions than he can make thousands 
turning pirate with them. So who'd turn pirate?"

266
00:27:31,440 --> 00:27:38,640
"Right." McLaurin nodded. "I see your point. 
Now before I'd accept your statements in re  

267
00:27:38,640 --> 00:27:43,360
the 'speed of light' thing, I'd want 
opinions from some IP physicists."

268
00:27:44,080 --> 00:27:46,080
"Then let's have a conference, because something's  

269
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:50,320
got to be done soon. I don't know why we 
haven't heard further from that fellow."

270
00:27:51,680 --> 00:27:58,960
"Privately—we have," McLaurin said in a slightly 
worried tone. "He was detected by the instruments  

271
00:27:58,960 --> 00:28:05,040
of every IP observatory I suspect. We got the 
reports but didn't know what to make of them.  

272
00:28:06,160 --> 00:28:10,800
They indicated so many funny things, they 
were sent in as accidental misreadings of  

273
00:28:10,800 --> 00:28:16,400
the instruments. But since all the observatories 
reported them, similar misreadings, at about the  

274
00:28:16,400 --> 00:28:21,920
same times, that is with variations of only 
a few hours, we thought something must have  

275
00:28:21,920 --> 00:28:28,400
been up. The only thing was the phenomena were 
reported progressively from Pluto to Neptune,  

276
00:28:28,400 --> 00:28:34,160
clear across the solar system, in a definite 
progression, but at a velocity of crossing  

277
00:28:34,160 --> 00:28:39,520
that didn't tie in with any conceivable force. 
They crossed faster than the velocity of light.  

278
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:46,720
That ship must have spent about half an hour off 
each planet before passing on to the next. And,  

279
00:28:46,720 --> 00:28:50,880
accepting your faster-than-light 
explanation, we can understand it."

280
00:28:51,760 --> 00:28:52,960
"Then I think you have proof."

281
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:56,080
"If we have, what would you do about it?"

282
00:28:57,520 --> 00:29:01,360
"Get to work on those 'misreadings' 
of the instruments for one thing,  

283
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:07,200
and for a second, and more important, line every 
IP ship with paraffin blocks six inches thick."

284
00:29:08,720 --> 00:29:09,600
"Paraffin—why?"

285
00:29:10,640 --> 00:29:16,480
"The easiest form of hydrogen to get. You can't 
use solid hydrogen, because that melts too easily.  

286
00:29:17,120 --> 00:29:22,640
Water can be turned into steam too easily, and 
requires more work. Paraffin is a solid that's  

287
00:29:22,640 --> 00:29:27,360
largely hydrogen. That's what they've always 
used on neutrons since they discovered them.  

288
00:29:28,320 --> 00:29:30,800
Confine your paraffin between tungsten walls,  

289
00:29:30,800 --> 00:29:34,080
and you'll stop the secondary 
protons as well as the neutrons."

290
00:29:35,440 --> 00:29:39,840
"Hmmm—I suppose so. How about 
seeing those physicists?"

291
00:29:40,560 --> 00:29:44,400
"I'd like to see them today, sir. The 
sooner you get started on this work,  

292
00:29:44,400 --> 00:29:46,240
the better it will be for the IP."

293
00:29:47,200 --> 00:29:51,120
"Having seen me, will you join up 
in the IP again?" asked McLaurin.

294
00:29:51,840 --> 00:29:56,960
"No, sir, I don't think I will. I have another 
field you know, in which I may be more useful.  

295
00:29:57,920 --> 00:30:01,680
Cole here's a better technician than 
fighter—and a darned good fighter, too—and  

296
00:30:02,320 --> 00:30:07,200
I think that an inexperienced space-captain is a 
lot less useful than a second-rate physicist at  

297
00:30:07,200 --> 00:30:13,520
work in a laboratory. If we hope to get anywhere, 
or for that matter, I suspect, stay anywhere,  

298
00:30:13,520 --> 00:30:16,160
we'll have to do a lot of 
research pretty promptly."

299
00:30:17,040 --> 00:30:18,720
"What's your explanation of that ship?"

300
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:27,360
"One of two things: an inventor of some 
other system trying out his latest toy, or an  

301
00:30:27,360 --> 00:30:33,440
expedition sent out by a planetary government for 
exploration. I favor the latter for two reasons:  

302
00:30:34,080 --> 00:30:40,320
that ship was big. No inventor would build a 
thing that size, requiring a crew of several  

303
00:30:40,320 --> 00:30:46,880
hundred men to try out his invention. A government 
would build just about that if they wanted to send  

304
00:30:46,880 --> 00:30:51,920
out an expedition. If it were an inventor, 
he'd be interested in meeting other people,  

305
00:30:51,920 --> 00:30:57,280
to see what they had in the way of science, and 
probably he'd want to do it in a peaceable way.  

306
00:30:58,800 --> 00:31:04,720
That fellow wasn't interested in peace, by 
any means. So I think it's a government ship,  

307
00:31:04,720 --> 00:31:10,560
and an unfriendly government. They sent that 
ship out either for scientific research,  

308
00:31:10,560 --> 00:31:17,040
for trade research and exploration, or for 
acquisitive exploration. If they were out for  

309
00:31:17,040 --> 00:31:21,440
scientific research, they'd proceed as would the 
inventor, to establish friendly communication.  

310
00:31:22,400 --> 00:31:28,720
If they were out for trade, the same would apply. 
If they were out for acquisitive exploration,  

311
00:31:28,720 --> 00:31:34,320
they'd investigate the planets, the sun, the 
people, only to the extent of learning how  

312
00:31:34,320 --> 00:31:40,640
best to overcome them. They'd want to get a sample 
of our people, and a sample of our weapons. They'd  

313
00:31:40,640 --> 00:31:47,520
want samples of our machinery, our literature and 
our technology. That's exactly what that ship got.

314
00:31:48,800 --> 00:31:55,040
"Somebody, somewhere out there in space, either 
doesn't like their home, or wants more home.  

315
00:31:55,920 --> 00:32:01,440
They've been out looking for one. I'll bet they 
sent out hundreds of expeditions to thousands  

316
00:32:01,440 --> 00:32:06,160
of nearby stars, gradually going further 
and further, seeking a planetary system.  

317
00:32:07,040 --> 00:32:09,600
This is probably the one and only one they found.  

318
00:32:10,320 --> 00:32:15,920
It's a good one too. It has planets at all 
temperatures, of all sizes. It is a fairly  

319
00:32:15,920 --> 00:32:20,880
compact one, it has a stable sun that will 
last far longer than any race can hope to."

320
00:32:22,800 --> 00:32:26,960
"Hmm—how can there be good 
and bad planetary systems?"  

321
00:32:26,960 --> 00:32:29,440
asked McLaurin. "I'd never thought of that."

322
00:32:30,800 --> 00:32:38,080
Kendall laughed. "Mighty easy. How'd you like to 
live on a planet of a Cepheid Variable? Pleasant  

323
00:32:38,080 --> 00:32:44,400
situation, with the radiation flaring up and down. 
How'd you like to live on a planet of Antares?  

324
00:32:44,960 --> 00:32:50,400
That blasted sun is so big, to have a comfortable 
planet you'd have to be at least ten billion miles  

325
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:56,320
out. Then if you had an interplanetary commerce, 
you'd have to struggle with orbits tens of  

326
00:32:56,320 --> 00:33:04,000
billions of miles across instead of mere millions. 
Further, you'd have a sun so blasted big,  

327
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:09,760
it would take an impossible amount of energy to 
lift the ship up from one planet to another. If  

328
00:33:09,760 --> 00:33:15,440
your trip was, say, twenty billions of miles to 
the next planet, you'd be fighting a gravity as  

329
00:33:15,440 --> 00:33:21,440
bad as the solar gravity at Earth here all the 
way—no decline with a little distance like that."

330
00:33:22,720 --> 00:33:30,800
"H-m-m-m—quite true. Then I should say that Mira 
would take the prize. It's a red giant, and it's  

331
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:37,600
an irregular variable. The sunlight there would 
be as unstable as the weather in New England. It's  

332
00:33:37,600 --> 00:33:44,240
almost as big as Antares, and it won't hold still. 
Now that would make a bad planetary system."

333
00:33:45,840 --> 00:33:50,000
"It would!" Kendall laughed. But as we know—he  

334
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:56,160
laughed too soon, and he shouldn't have used 
the conditional. He should have said, "It does!"

335
00:34:13,600 --> 00:34:23,200
Gresth Gkae, Commander of Expeditionary Force 
93, of the Planet Sthor, was returning homeward  

336
00:34:23,200 --> 00:34:31,360
with joyful mind. In the lock of his great ship, 
lay the T-247. In her cargo holds lay various  

337
00:34:31,360 --> 00:34:38,000
items of machinery, mining supplies, foods, and 
records. And in her log books lay the records  

338
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:43,120
of many readings on the nine larger planets 
of a highly satisfactory planetary system.

339
00:34:44,800 --> 00:34:51,680
Gresth Gkae had spent no less than three 
ultra-wearing years going from one sun to another  

340
00:34:51,680 --> 00:34:58,000
in a definitely mapped out section of space. He 
had investigated only eleven stars in that time,  

341
00:34:58,800 --> 00:35:04,880
eleven stars, progressively further from the 
titanic red-flaming sun he knew as "the" sun.  

342
00:35:06,560 --> 00:35:13,360
He knew it as "the" sun, and had several other 
appellations for it. Mira was so-named by  

343
00:35:13,360 --> 00:35:19,840
Earthmen because it was indeed a "wonder" 
star, in Latin, mirare means "to wonder."  

344
00:35:21,200 --> 00:35:25,200
Irregularly, and for no apparent reason 
it would change its rate of radiation.  

345
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:33,200
So far as those inhabitants of Sthor and her 
sister world Asthor knew, there was no reason. It  

346
00:35:33,200 --> 00:35:40,960
just did it. Perhaps with malicious intent to be 
annoying. If so, it was exceptionally successful.  

347
00:35:41,760 --> 00:35:49,120
Sthor and Asthor experienced, periodically, 
a young ice age. When Mira decided to take  

348
00:35:49,120 --> 00:35:54,960
a rest, Sthor and Asthor froze up, from 
the poles most of the way to the equators.  

349
00:35:55,680 --> 00:36:01,120
Then Mira would stretch herself a little, 
move about restlessly and Sthor and Asthor  

350
00:36:01,120 --> 00:36:05,840
would become uninhabitably hot, anywhere 
within twenty degrees of the equator.

351
00:36:07,120 --> 00:36:12,080
Those Sthorian people had evolved in a way 
that made the conditions endurable for savage  

352
00:36:12,080 --> 00:36:17,600
or uncivilized people, but when a scientific 
civilization with a well-ordered mode of  

353
00:36:17,600 --> 00:36:22,800
existence tried to establish itself, 
Mira was all sorts of a nuisance.

354
00:36:24,240 --> 00:36:31,280
Gresth Gkae was a peculiar individual to human 
ways of thinking. He stood some seven feet tall,  

355
00:36:31,280 --> 00:36:37,120
on his strange, double-kneed legs and his four 
toed feet. His body was covered with little,  

356
00:36:37,120 --> 00:36:42,800
short feather-like things that moved now with 
a volition of their own. They were moving very  

357
00:36:42,800 --> 00:36:49,200
slowly and regularly. The space-ship was heated 
to a comfortable temperature, and the little fans  

358
00:36:49,200 --> 00:36:55,840
were helping to cool Gresth Gkae. Had it been 
cold, every little feather would have lain down  

359
00:36:55,840 --> 00:37:00,400
close against its neighbors, forming an 
admirable, wind-proof and cold-proof blanket.

360
00:37:01,680 --> 00:37:09,280
Nature, on Sthor, had original ideas of 
arrangement too. Sthorians possessed two eyes—one  

361
00:37:09,840 --> 00:37:14,720
directly above the other, in the center 
of their faces. The face was so long,  

362
00:37:14,720 --> 00:37:20,640
and narrow, it resembled a blunt hatchet, with 
the two eyes on the edge. To counter-balance  

363
00:37:20,640 --> 00:37:25,360
this vertical arrangement of the eyes, the 
nostrils had been separated some four inches,  

364
00:37:25,920 --> 00:37:31,920
with one on each of the sloping cheeks. His 
ears were little pink-flesh cups on short,  

365
00:37:31,920 --> 00:37:38,720
muscular stems. His mouth was narrow, and small, 
but armed with quite solid teeth adapted to his  

366
00:37:38,720 --> 00:37:44,000
diet, a diet consisting of almost anything 
any creature had ever considered edible.  

367
00:37:45,600 --> 00:37:52,320
Like most successful forms of intelligent life, 
Gresth Gkae was omnivorous. An intelligent form  

368
00:37:52,320 --> 00:37:58,400
of life is necessarily adaptable, and adaptation 
meant being able to eat what was at hand.

369
00:37:59,680 --> 00:38:03,840
One of his eyes, the upper one, was 
fully twice the size of the lower one.  

370
00:38:04,480 --> 00:38:10,320
This was his telescopic eye. The lower, 
or microscopic eye was adapted to work  

371
00:38:10,320 --> 00:38:14,160
for which a human being would have 
required a low power microscope,  

372
00:38:14,880 --> 00:38:20,320
the upper eye possessed a more normal power of 
vision, plus considerable telescopic powers.

373
00:38:21,760 --> 00:38:28,000
Gresth Gkae was using it now to look ahead in the 
blank of space to where gigantic Mira appeared.  

374
00:38:28,960 --> 00:38:34,160
On his screens now, Mira appeared deep 
violet, for he was approaching at a speed  

375
00:38:34,160 --> 00:38:38,720
greater than that of light, and even this 
projected light of Mira was badly distorted.

376
00:38:39,760 --> 00:38:43,840
"The distance is half a light-year now, 
sir," reported the navigation officer.

377
00:38:44,800 --> 00:38:49,520
"Reduce the speed, then, to normal velocity for 
these ranges. What reserve of fuel have we?"

378
00:38:50,240 --> 00:38:54,480
"Less than one thousand pounds. We 
will barely be able to stop. We were  

379
00:38:54,480 --> 00:38:57,920
too free in the use of our weapons, I 
fear," replied the Chief Technician.

380
00:38:59,120 --> 00:39:05,600
"Well, what would you? We needed those things in 
our reports. Besides, we could extract fuel from  

381
00:39:05,600 --> 00:39:11,440
that ore we took on at Planet Nine of Phahlo. 
It is merely that I wish speed in the return."

382
00:39:13,120 --> 00:39:18,560
"As we all do. How soon do you believe the 
Council will proceed against the new system?"

383
00:39:19,680 --> 00:39:25,440
"It will be fully a year, I fear. They must gather 
the expeditions together, and re-equip the ships.  

384
00:39:26,080 --> 00:39:28,560
It will be a long time before 
all will have come in."

385
00:39:29,760 --> 00:39:32,480
"Could they not send fast ships 
after them to recall them?"

386
00:39:33,520 --> 00:39:37,600
"Could they have traced us as we 
wove our way from Thart to Karst  

387
00:39:37,600 --> 00:39:41,920
to Raloork to Phahlo? It would be impossible."

388
00:39:41,920 --> 00:39:48,160
Steadily the great ship had been boring on her 
way. Mira had been a disc for nearly two days,  

389
00:39:48,800 --> 00:39:55,360
gigantic, two-hundred-and-fifty-million-mile Mira 
took a great deal of dwarfing by distance to lose  

390
00:39:55,360 --> 00:40:01,120
her disc. Even at the Twin Planets, eight thousand 
two hundred and fifty millions of miles out,  

391
00:40:01,680 --> 00:40:07,600
Mira covered half the sky, it seemed, 
red and angry. Sometimes, though,  

392
00:40:07,600 --> 00:40:14,400
to the disgust of the Sthorians it was 
just red-faced and lazy. Then Sthor froze.

393
00:40:16,720 --> 00:40:20,720
"Grih is in a descendant stage," said 
the navigation officer presently.  

394
00:40:21,360 --> 00:40:23,840
"Sthor will be cold when we arrive."

395
00:40:24,880 --> 00:40:28,480
"It will warm quickly enough 
with our news!" Gresth laughed.  

396
00:40:29,360 --> 00:40:37,760
"A system—a delightful system—discovered. A system 
of many close-grouped planets. Why think—from one  

397
00:40:37,760 --> 00:40:43,280
side of that system to the other is less of a 
distance than from Ansthat, our first planet's  

398
00:40:43,280 --> 00:40:50,400
orbit, to Insthor's orbit! That sun, as we know, 
is steady and warm. All will be well, when we have  

399
00:40:50,400 --> 00:40:56,240
eliminated that rather peculiar race. Odd, that 
they should, in some ways, be so nearly like us!  

400
00:40:57,120 --> 00:41:03,120
Nearly Sthorian in build. I would not have 
expected it. Though they did have some  

401
00:41:03,120 --> 00:41:11,600
amazing peculiarities! Imagine—two eyes just 
alike, and in a horizontal row. And that flat  

402
00:41:11,600 --> 00:41:16,640
face. They looked as though they had suffered some 
accident that smashed the front of the face in.  

403
00:41:17,440 --> 00:41:24,160
And also the peculiar beak-like projection. Why 
should a race ever develop so amazing a projection  

404
00:41:24,160 --> 00:41:29,440
in so peculiar and exposed a position? 
It sticks out inviting attack and injury.  

405
00:41:30,160 --> 00:41:36,400
Right in the middle of the face. And to make it 
worse, there is the air-channel, and the only air  

406
00:41:36,400 --> 00:41:42,880
channel. Why, one minor injury to the throat would 
be certain to damage that passage beyond repair,  

407
00:41:42,880 --> 00:41:48,960
and bring death. Yet such relatively unimportant 
things as ears, and eyes are doubled.  

408
00:41:49,600 --> 00:41:54,640
Surely you would expect that so important a member 
as the air-passage would be doubled for safety.

409
00:41:55,440 --> 00:42:01,280
"Those strange, awkward arms and legs were 
what puzzled me. I have been attempting to  

410
00:42:01,280 --> 00:42:06,560
manipulate myself as they must be forced to, 
and I cannot see how delicate or accurate  

411
00:42:06,560 --> 00:42:12,400
manual manipulation would be possible with 
those rigid, inflexible arms. In some ways I  

412
00:42:12,400 --> 00:42:18,560
feel they must have had clever minds to overcome 
so great a handicap to constructive work. But I  

413
00:42:18,560 --> 00:42:23,280
suppose single joints in the arms become as 
natural to them as our own more mobile two.

414
00:42:24,720 --> 00:42:29,840
"I wonder if life in any intelligent form wouldn't 
develop somewhat similar formations, though.  

415
00:42:30,400 --> 00:42:35,840
Think, in all parts of Sthor, before men 
became civilized and developed communication,  

416
00:42:36,480 --> 00:42:42,240
even so much as twenty thousand years ago, our 
records show that seats and chairs were much  

417
00:42:42,240 --> 00:42:47,760
as they are today, and much as they are, 
in all places among all groups. Then too,  

418
00:42:47,760 --> 00:42:52,640
the eye has developed in many different species, 
and always reached much the same structure.  

419
00:42:53,680 --> 00:42:57,440
When a thing is intended and 
developed to serve a given purpose,  

420
00:42:57,440 --> 00:43:03,040
no matter who develops it, or where or how, is 
it not apt to have similar shapes and parts?  

421
00:43:03,840 --> 00:43:10,160
A chair must have legs, and a seat and arm-rests 
and a back. You may vary their nature and their  

422
00:43:10,160 --> 00:43:16,960
shape, but not widely, and they must be there. 
An eye must, anywhere, have a sensitive retina,  

423
00:43:16,960 --> 00:43:21,520
an adjustable lens, and an adjustable device 
for controlling the entrance of light.  

424
00:43:22,400 --> 00:43:26,960
Similarly there are certain functions that 
the body of an intelligent creature must serve  

425
00:43:26,960 --> 00:43:32,960
which naturally tend to make intelligent 
creatures similar. He must have a tool—the hand—"

426
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:37,280
"Yes, yes—I see your point. It must be so, for  

427
00:43:37,280 --> 00:43:40,560
surely these creatures out there 
are strange enough in other ways."

428
00:43:41,280 --> 00:43:43,920
"But tell me, have you 
calculated when we shall land?"

429
00:43:45,760 --> 00:43:47,760
"In twelve hours, thirty-three minutes, sir."

430
00:43:49,680 --> 00:43:54,160
Eleven hours later, the expedition ship 
had slowed to a normal space-speed.  

431
00:43:55,040 --> 00:44:00,800
On her left hung the giant globe of Asthor, 
rotating slowly, moving slowly in her orbit.  

432
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:08,480
Directly ahead, Sthor loomed even greater. 
Tiny Teelan, the thousand-mile diameter  

433
00:44:08,480 --> 00:44:14,400
moon of the Insthor system shone dull red 
in the reflected light of gigantic Mira.  

434
00:44:15,120 --> 00:44:21,840
Mira herself was gigantic, red and menacing across 
eight and a quarter billions of miles of space.

435
00:44:23,280 --> 00:44:26,640
One hundred thousand miles apart, the twin worlds  

436
00:44:26,640 --> 00:44:32,800
Sthor and Asthor rotated about their common 
center of gravity, eternally facing each other.  

437
00:44:33,840 --> 00:44:39,360
Ten million miles from their common center 
of gravity, Teelan rotated in a vast orbit.

438
00:44:40,800 --> 00:44:48,000
Sthor and Asthor were capped at each pole now 
by gigantic white icecaps. Mira was sulking,  

439
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:50,400
and as a consequence the planets were freezing.

440
00:44:51,760 --> 00:44:58,080
The expedition ship sank slowly toward Sthor. 
A swarm of smaller craft had flown up at its  

441
00:44:58,080 --> 00:45:04,320
approach to meet it. A gaily-colored small 
ship marked the official greeting-ship.  

442
00:45:04,320 --> 00:45:10,480
Gresth had withheld his news purposely. Now 
suddenly he began broadcasting it from the  

443
00:45:10,480 --> 00:45:15,600
powerful transmitter on his ship. As the 
words came through on a thousand sets,  

444
00:45:15,600 --> 00:45:21,040
all the little ships began to whirl, dance 
and break out into glowing, sparkling lights.  

445
00:45:21,840 --> 00:45:30,000
On Sthor and Asthor even commotions began to be 
visible. A new planetary system had been found—  

446
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:34,480
They could move! Their overflowing 
populations could be spread out!

447
00:45:35,440 --> 00:45:42,160
The whole Insthor system went mad with delight 
as the great Expeditionary Ship settled downward.

448
00:46:01,040 --> 00:46:05,200
There was a glint of humor in Buck 
Kendall's eyes as he passed the sheet  

449
00:46:05,200 --> 00:46:10,480
over to McLaurin. Commander McLaurin looked 
down the columns with twinkling eyes.

450
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:18,400
"'Petition to establish the Lunar Mining 
Bank,'" he read. "What a bank! Officers:  

451
00:46:18,400 --> 00:46:21,680
President, General James Logan, late of the IP;  

452
00:46:22,720 --> 00:46:30,480
Vice-president, Colonel Warren Gerardhi, also 
late of the IP; Staff, consists of 90% ex-IP men,  

453
00:46:30,480 --> 00:46:35,760
and a few scattered accountants. Designed 
by the well-known designer of IP stations,  

454
00:46:35,760 --> 00:46:42,080
Colonel Richard Murray." Commander McLaurin 
looked up at Kendall with a broad grin.  

455
00:46:42,080 --> 00:46:46,800
"And you actually got Interplanetary Life 
to give you a mortgage on the structure?"

456
00:46:47,680 --> 00:46:53,600
"Why not? It'll cut cost fifty-eight millions, 
with its twelve-foot tungsten-beryllium walls and  

457
00:46:53,600 --> 00:46:58,800
the heavy defense weapons against those terrible 
pirates. You know we must defend our property."

458
00:47:00,080 --> 00:47:03,600
"With the thing you're setting up out 
there on Luna, you could more readily  

459
00:47:03,600 --> 00:47:08,080
wipe out the IP than anything else 
I know of. Any new defense ideas?"

460
00:47:08,960 --> 00:47:13,920
"Plenty. Did you get any further appropriations 
from the IP Appropriations Board?"

461
00:47:14,640 --> 00:47:20,160
McLaurin looked sour. "No. The 
dear taxpayers might object,  

462
00:47:20,160 --> 00:47:25,120
and those thickheaded, clogged rockets on the 
Board can't see your data on the Stranger.  

463
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:30,800
They gave me just ten millions, and that only 
because you demonstrated you could shoot every  

464
00:47:30,800 --> 00:47:35,680
living thing out of the latest IP cruiser 
with that neutron gun of yours. By the way,  

465
00:47:36,320 --> 00:47:39,120
they may kick when I don't 
install more than a few of those."

466
00:47:40,160 --> 00:47:44,960
"Let 'em. You can stall for a few months. 
You'll need that money more for other purposes.  

467
00:47:45,600 --> 00:47:47,360
You've installed that paraffin lining?"

468
00:47:48,160 --> 00:47:52,480
"Yes—I got a report on that of 'finished' 
last week. How have you made out?"

469
00:47:53,520 --> 00:47:56,800
Buck Kendall's face fell. "Not so hot.  

470
00:47:57,520 --> 00:48:01,520
Devin's been the biggest help—he did most 
of the work on that neutron gun really—"

471
00:48:02,080 --> 00:48:06,000
"After," McLaurin interrupted, "you told him how."

472
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:10,320
"—but we're pretty well stuck now, it 
seems. You'll be off duty tomorrow evening,  

473
00:48:10,320 --> 00:48:15,520
can't you drop around to the lab? We're going to 
try out a new system for releasing atomic energy."

474
00:48:16,960 --> 00:48:21,280
"Isn't that a pretty faint hope? We've been 
trying to get it for three centuries now,  

475
00:48:21,280 --> 00:48:25,360
and haven't yet. What chance at 
it within a year or so?—which  

476
00:48:25,360 --> 00:48:28,080
is the time you allow yourself 
before the Stranger returns."

477
00:48:29,440 --> 00:48:37,120
"It is, I'll admit that. But there's another 
factor, not to be forgotten. The data we got  

478
00:48:37,120 --> 00:48:42,480
from correlating those 'misreadings' 
from the various IP posts mean a lot.  

479
00:48:43,200 --> 00:48:47,760
We are working on an entirely 
different trail now. You come on out,  

480
00:48:47,760 --> 00:48:51,840
and you can see our new apparatus. They 
are working on tremendous voltages,  

481
00:48:51,840 --> 00:48:57,520
and hoping to smash the thing by a brutal 
bombardment of terrific voltage. We're trying,  

482
00:48:57,520 --> 00:49:03,120
thanks to the results of those instruments, to get 
results with small, terrifically intense fields."

483
00:49:04,640 --> 00:49:06,640
"How do you know that's their general system?"

484
00:49:07,360 --> 00:49:10,160
"They left traces on the 
records of the post instruments.  

485
00:49:10,720 --> 00:49:16,240
These records show such intensities as 
we never got. They have atomic energy,  

486
00:49:16,240 --> 00:49:22,240
necessarily, and they might have had material 
energy, actual destruction of matter,  

487
00:49:22,240 --> 00:49:28,080
but apparently, from the field readings it's the 
former. To be able to make those tremendous hops,  

488
00:49:28,080 --> 00:49:33,680
light-years in length, they needed a real 
store of energy. They have accumulators,  

489
00:49:33,680 --> 00:49:38,080
of course, but I don't think they could store 
enough power by the system they use to do it."

490
00:49:40,080 --> 00:49:44,080
"Well, how's your trick 'bank' out on 
Luna, despite its twelve-foot walls,  

491
00:49:44,080 --> 00:49:46,000
going to stand an atomic explosion?"

492
00:49:47,280 --> 00:49:54,400
"More protective devices to come is our only hope. 
I'm working on three trails: atomic energy, some  

493
00:49:54,400 --> 00:49:59,920
type of magnetic shield that will stop any moving 
material particle, and their faster-than-light  

494
00:49:59,920 --> 00:50:06,400
thing. Also, that fortress—I mean, of course, 
bank—is going to have a lot of lead-lined rooms."

495
00:50:08,080 --> 00:50:12,000
"I wish I could use the remaining money the 
Board gave me to lead-line a lot of those  

496
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:17,280
IP ships," said McLaurin wistfully. "Can't 
you make a gamma-ray bomb of some sort?"

497
00:50:18,560 --> 00:50:23,760
"Not without their atomic energy release. With it, 
of course, it's easy to flood a region with rays.  

498
00:50:24,320 --> 00:50:27,920
It'll be a million times worse than 
radium 'C,' which is bad enough."

499
00:50:29,440 --> 00:50:33,920
"Well, I'll send through this petition 
for armaments. They'll pass it all right,  

500
00:50:33,920 --> 00:50:40,320
I think. They may get some kicks from old Jacob 
Ezra Stubbs. Jacob Ezra doesn't believe in  

501
00:50:40,320 --> 00:50:46,480
anything war-like. I wish they'd find some way to 
keep him off of the Arms Petition Board. He might  

502
00:50:46,480 --> 00:50:54,240
just as well stay home and let 'em vote his ticket 
uniformly 'nay.'" Buck Kendall left with a laugh.

503
00:50:54,240 --> 00:50:58,400
Buck Kendall had his troubles though. 
When he had reached Earth again,  

504
00:50:58,400 --> 00:51:02,480
he found that his properties totaled one 
hundred and three million dollars, roughly.  

505
00:51:03,440 --> 00:51:07,840
One doesn't sell properties of that 
magnitude, one borrows against them.  

506
00:51:08,560 --> 00:51:14,000
But to all intents and purposes, Buck Kendall 
owned two half-completed ship's hulls in the  

507
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:20,240
Baldwin Spaceship Yards, a great deal of massive 
metal work on its way to Luna, and contracts  

508
00:51:20,240 --> 00:51:25,600
for some very extensive work on a "bank." 
Beyond that, about eleven million was left.

509
00:51:27,920 --> 00:51:31,520
A large portion of the money had 
been invested in a laboratory,  

510
00:51:31,520 --> 00:51:38,000
the like of which the world had never seen. It was 
devoted exclusively to physics, and principally  

511
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:44,000
the physics of destruction. Dr. Paul Devin 
was the Director, Cole was in charge of the  

512
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:48,400
technical work, and Buck Kendall was free 
to do all the work he thought needed doing.

513
00:51:49,760 --> 00:51:54,160
Returned to his laboratory, he looked sourly 
at the bench on which seven mechanicians were  

514
00:51:54,160 --> 00:51:59,280
working. The ninth successive experiment 
on the release of atomic energy had failed.  

515
00:52:00,160 --> 00:52:06,640
The tenth was in process of construction. A 
heavy pure tungsten dome, three feet in diameter,  

516
00:52:06,640 --> 00:52:10,800
three inches thick, was being 
lowered over a clear insulum dome,  

517
00:52:10,800 --> 00:52:16,800
a foot smaller. Inside, the real apparatus was 
arranged around the little pool of mercury.  

518
00:52:17,440 --> 00:52:23,760
From it, two massive tungsten-copper alloy 
conductors led through the insulum housing,  

519
00:52:23,760 --> 00:52:29,920
and outside. These, so Kendall had hoped, 
would surge with the power of broken atoms,  

520
00:52:30,560 --> 00:52:34,080
but he was beginning to believe rather 
bitterly, they would never do so.

521
00:52:35,440 --> 00:52:38,400
Buck went on to his offices, 
and the main calculator room.  

522
00:52:39,280 --> 00:52:42,720
There were ten calculator tables 
here, two of them in operation now.

523
00:52:43,920 --> 00:52:45,840
"Hello, Devin. Getting on?"

524
00:52:46,560 --> 00:52:52,880
"No," said Devin bitterly, "I'm getting off. 
Look at these results." He brought over a sheaf  

525
00:52:52,880 --> 00:52:59,200
of graphs, with explanatory tables attached. 
Rapidly Buck ran through them with him. Most  

526
00:52:59,200 --> 00:53:03,120
of them were graphs of functions of light, 
considered as a wave in these experiments.

527
00:53:05,360 --> 00:53:10,240
"H-m-m-m—not very encouraging. Looks like 
you've got the field—but it just snaps shut  

528
00:53:10,240 --> 00:53:15,760
on itself and won't work. The lack of volume 
makes it break down, if you establish it,  

529
00:53:15,760 --> 00:53:19,680
and makes it impossible to establish in the 
first place without the energy of matter.  

530
00:53:20,640 --> 00:53:24,480
Not so hot. That's certainly cock-eyed somewhere."

531
00:53:25,520 --> 00:53:27,840
"I'm not. The math may be."

532
00:53:28,400 --> 00:53:32,880
"Well"—Kendall grinned—"it amounts 
to the same thing. The point is,  

533
00:53:32,880 --> 00:53:39,840
light doesn't. Let's run over that theory 
again. Light is not only magnetic; but electric.  

534
00:53:40,560 --> 00:53:45,680
Somehow it transforms electric fields 
cyclically into magnetic fields and back again.  

535
00:53:46,480 --> 00:53:53,200
Now what we want to do is to transform an electric 
into a magnetic field and have it stay there.  

536
00:53:53,760 --> 00:53:59,360
That's the first step. The second thing, is to 
have the lines of magnetic force you develop,  

537
00:53:59,360 --> 00:54:05,280
lie down like a sheath around the ship, instead of 
standing out like the hairs on an angry cat, the  

538
00:54:05,280 --> 00:54:11,120
way they want to. That means turning them ninety 
degrees, and turning an electric into a magnetic  

539
00:54:11,120 --> 00:54:18,320
field means turning the space-strain ninety 
degrees. Light evidently forms a magnetic field  

540
00:54:18,320 --> 00:54:23,840
whose lines of force reach along its direction 
of motion, so that's your starting point."

541
00:54:24,720 --> 00:54:31,280
"Yes, and that," growled Devin, "seems to be the 
finishing point. Quite definitely and clearly,  

542
00:54:31,280 --> 00:54:37,840
the graph looped down to zero. In other words, the 
field closed in on itself, and destroyed itself."

543
00:54:39,280 --> 00:54:40,720
"Light doesn't vanish."

544
00:54:41,920 --> 00:54:44,080
"I'll make you all the lights you want."

545
00:54:44,080 --> 00:54:46,960
"I simply mean there must be 
something that will stop it."

546
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:52,880
"Certainly. Transform it back to electric 
field before it gets a chance to close in,  

547
00:54:52,880 --> 00:54:54,880
then repeat the process—the way light does."

548
00:54:56,240 --> 00:55:01,600
"That wouldn't make such a good magnetic shield. 
Every time that field started pulsing out through  

549
00:55:01,600 --> 00:55:07,280
the walls of the ship it would generate heat. 
We want a permanent field that will stay on the  

550
00:55:07,280 --> 00:55:12,240
job out there. I wonder if you couldn't make 
a conductor device that would open that field  

551
00:55:12,240 --> 00:55:16,320
out—some special type of oscillating 
field that would keep it open."

552
00:55:18,480 --> 00:55:21,680
"H-m-m-m—that's an angle I 
might try. Any suggestions?"

553
00:55:22,960 --> 00:55:26,960
Kendall had suggestions, and rapidly 
he outlined a development that appeared  

554
00:55:26,960 --> 00:55:30,480
from some of the earlier mathematics on 
light, and might be what they wanted.

555
00:55:32,160 --> 00:55:37,520
Kendall, however, had problems of his own 
to work on. The question of atomic energy he  

556
00:55:37,520 --> 00:55:42,800
was leaving alone, till the present experiment 
either succeeded, or, as he rather suspected,  

557
00:55:42,800 --> 00:55:48,480
failed as had its predecessors. His present 
problem was to develop more fully some  

558
00:55:48,480 --> 00:55:53,760
interesting lines of research he had run across in 
investigating mathematically the trick of turning  

559
00:55:53,760 --> 00:55:59,520
electric to magnetic fields and then turning them 
back again. It might be that along this line he  

560
00:55:59,520 --> 00:56:04,320
would find the answer to the speed greater than 
that of light. At any rate, he was interested.

561
00:56:06,160 --> 00:56:11,040
He worked the rest of that day, and most of the 
next on that line—till he ran it into the ground  

562
00:56:11,040 --> 00:56:21,280
with a pair of equations that ended with the 
expression: dx.dv=h/(4πm). Then Kendall looked  

563
00:56:21,280 --> 00:56:25,920
at them for a long moment, then he sighed 
gently and threw them into a file cabinet.  

564
00:56:26,720 --> 00:56:32,560
Heisenberg's Uncertainty. He'd reduced the thing 
to a form that simply told him it was beyond  

565
00:56:32,560 --> 00:56:38,400
the limits of certainty and he ran it into the 
normal, natural uncertainty inevitable in Nature.

566
00:56:40,480 --> 00:56:45,120
Anyway he had real work to do now. The 
machine was about ready for his attention.  

567
00:56:45,840 --> 00:56:49,520
The mechanicians had finished putting 
it in shape for demonstration and trial.  

568
00:56:50,160 --> 00:56:54,880
He himself would have to test it over the rest of 
the afternoon and arrange for power and so forth.

569
00:56:56,320 --> 00:57:00,640
By evening, when Commander McLaurin called 
around with some of the other investors in  

570
00:57:00,640 --> 00:57:06,000
Kendall's "bank" on Luna, the thing was 
already started, warming up. The fields  

571
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:09,760
were being fed and the various scientists 
of the group were watching with interest.  

572
00:57:10,800 --> 00:57:15,360
Power was flowing in already at a rate of nearly 
one hundred thousand horsepower per minute,  

573
00:57:15,920 --> 00:57:22,000
thanks to a special line given them by New York 
Power (a Kendall property). At ten o'clock they  

574
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:27,760
were beginning to expect the reaction to start. By 
this time the fields weren't gaining in intensity  

575
00:57:27,760 --> 00:57:33,280
very rapidly, a maximum intensity had been reached 
that should, they felt, break the atoms soon.

576
00:57:34,720 --> 00:57:40,640
At eleven-thirty, through the little view window, 
Buck Kendall saw something that made him cry out  

577
00:57:40,640 --> 00:57:47,280
in amazement. The mercury metal in the receiver, 
behind its layers of screening was beginning  

578
00:57:47,280 --> 00:57:54,160
to glow, with a dull reddish light, and little 
solidifications were appearing in it! Eagerly the  

579
00:57:54,160 --> 00:58:00,240
men looked, as the solidifications spread slowly, 
like crystals growing in an evaporating solution.

580
00:58:01,520 --> 00:58:08,080
Twelve o'clock came and went, and one o'clock 
and two o'clock. Still the slow crystallization  

581
00:58:08,080 --> 00:58:15,440
went on. Buck Kendall was casting furtive glances 
at the kilowatt-hour meter. It stood at a figure  

582
00:58:15,440 --> 00:58:22,160
that represented twenty-seven thousand dollars' 
worth of power. Long since the power rate had  

583
00:58:22,160 --> 00:58:27,120
been increased to the maximum available, as 
the power plant's normal load reduced as the  

584
00:58:27,120 --> 00:58:35,040
morning hours came. Surely, this time something 
would start, but Buck had two worries. If all  

585
00:58:35,040 --> 00:58:40,000
the enormous amount of energy they had poured 
in there decided to release itself at once—

586
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:45,440
And at any rate, Buck saw they'd never dare 
to let a generator stop, once it was started!

587
00:58:46,080 --> 00:58:52,560
The men were a tense group around the machine at 
three-fifteen a.m. There remained only a tiny,  

588
00:58:52,560 --> 00:58:58,080
dancing globule of silvery mercury skittering 
around on the sharp, needle-like crystals  

589
00:58:58,080 --> 00:59:03,840
of the dull red metal that had resulted. 
Slowly that skittering drop was shrinking—

590
00:59:05,280 --> 00:59:09,280
Three twenty-two and a half a.m. 
saw the last fraction of it vanish.  

591
00:59:10,240 --> 00:59:14,160
Tensely the men stared into the 
machine—backing off slowly—watching  

592
00:59:14,720 --> 00:59:20,240
the meters on the board. At nearly eighty 
thousand volts the power had been fed into it.

593
00:59:21,200 --> 00:59:25,040
The power continued to flow, 
and a growing halo of intense  

594
00:59:25,040 --> 00:59:32,000
violet light appeared suddenly on those red, 
needle-like crystals, a swiftly expanding halo—

595
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:37,120
Without a sound, without the slightest 
disturbance, the halo vanished,  

596
00:59:37,120 --> 00:59:41,760
and softly, gently, the 
needle-like crystals relapsed,  

597
00:59:41,760 --> 00:59:46,560
melted away, and a dull pool of 
metallic mercury rested in the receiver.

598
00:59:47,760 --> 00:59:51,040
At eighty thousand volts, power was flowing in—

599
00:59:51,680 --> 00:59:53,840
And it didn't even sparkle.

600
01:00:13,920 --> 01:00:19,440
The apparatus of the magnetic shield had been 
completed two days later, and set up in Buck's  

601
01:00:19,440 --> 01:00:25,680
own laboratory. On the bench was the powerful, but 
small, little projector of the straight magnetic  

602
01:00:25,680 --> 01:00:31,920
field, simply a specially designed accumulator, a 
super-condenser, and the peculiar apparatus Devin  

603
01:00:31,920 --> 01:00:36,640
had designed to distort the electric field 
through ninety degrees to a magnetic field.  

604
01:00:37,200 --> 01:00:42,240
Behind this was a curious, paraboloid 
projector made up of hundreds of tiny,  

605
01:00:42,240 --> 01:00:48,880
carefully orientated coils. This was Buck's own 
contribution. They were ready for the tests.

606
01:00:50,560 --> 01:00:55,920
"I would invite McLaurin in to see this," said 
Kendall looking at them, and then across the  

607
01:00:55,920 --> 01:01:00,720
room bitterly toward the alleged atomic 
power apparatus on the opposite bench.  

608
01:01:01,680 --> 01:01:08,080
"I think it will work. But after that—" He stared, 
glaring, at the heavy tungsten dome with its  

609
01:01:08,080 --> 01:01:14,000
heavy tungsten contacts, across which the flame of 
released atomic energy was supposed to have leapt.  

610
01:01:15,280 --> 01:01:19,760
"That was probably the flattest 
flop any experiment ever flopped."

611
01:01:21,200 --> 01:01:24,960
"Well—it didn't blow up. That's 
one comfort," suggested Devin.

612
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:32,160
"I wish it had. Then at least it would have 
shown some response. The only response shown,  

613
01:01:32,160 --> 01:01:37,840
actually, was shown on the power meter. It damn 
near wore out the bearings turning so fast."

614
01:01:38,960 --> 01:01:44,160
"Personally, I prefer the lack of action." Devin 
laughed. "Have you got that circuit hooked up?"

615
01:01:45,280 --> 01:01:49,840
"Right," sighed Kendall, turning back to 
the work in hand. "Is Douglass in on this?"

616
01:01:51,040 --> 01:01:55,680
"Yes—in the next room. He'll let us know when 
he's ready. He's setting up those instruments."

617
01:01:56,880 --> 01:02:01,520
Douglass, a young junior physicist, 
late of the IP Physics Department,  

618
01:02:01,520 --> 01:02:04,800
stuck his head in the door and announced 
his instruments were all set up.

619
01:02:05,440 --> 01:02:08,000
"Keep an eye on them. They'll 
move somehow, at any rate.  

620
01:02:08,720 --> 01:02:11,840
This thing couldn't go as flat 
as that atom-buster of mine."

621
01:02:12,880 --> 01:02:17,040
Carefully Kendall made a few last-minute 
adjustments on the limiting relays,  

622
01:02:17,760 --> 01:02:22,800
and took up his position at the power board. 
Devin took his place near the apparatus,  

623
01:02:22,800 --> 01:02:27,920
with another series of instruments, similar to 
those Douglass was now watching in the next room,  

624
01:02:27,920 --> 01:02:34,240
some thirty feet away, through the two-inch 
metal wall. "Ready," called Kendall.

625
01:02:34,240 --> 01:02:39,440
The switch shot home. Instantly Kendall, 
Devin, and all the men in the building  

626
01:02:39,440 --> 01:02:41,920
jumped some six feet from their former positions.  

627
01:02:42,720 --> 01:02:48,880
A monstrous roar of sound crashed out in that 
laboratory that thundered from one wall to  

628
01:02:48,880 --> 01:02:55,600
the other, and bellowed in a Titan's fury. It 
thundered and growled, it bellowed and howled,  

629
01:02:55,600 --> 01:03:00,000
the walls shook with the march and 
counter-march of crashing waves of sound.

630
01:03:00,640 --> 01:03:06,960
And a ten-foot wavering flame of blue-white, 
bellying electric fire shuddered up to the  

631
01:03:06,960 --> 01:03:13,120
ceiling from the contact points of the alleged 
atomic generator. The heat, pouring out from the  

632
01:03:13,120 --> 01:03:19,440
flashing, roaring arc sent prickles of aching 
burns over Kendall's skin. For ten seconds he  

633
01:03:19,440 --> 01:03:27,600
stood in utter, paralyzed surprise as his flop of 
flops bellowed its anger at his disdain. Then he  

634
01:03:27,600 --> 01:03:32,320
leapt to the power board and shut off the roaring 
thing, by cutting the switch that had started it.

635
01:03:33,440 --> 01:03:37,120
"Spirits of Space! Did that come to life!"

636
01:03:38,720 --> 01:03:41,120
"Atomic Energy!" Devin cried.

637
01:03:41,680 --> 01:03:47,040
"Atomic energy, hell. That's my thirty thousand 
dollars' worth of power breaking loose again,"  

638
01:03:47,040 --> 01:03:53,680
chortled Kendall. "We missed the atomic energy, 
but, sweet boy, what an accumulator we stubbed our  

639
01:03:53,680 --> 01:04:01,600
toes on! I wondered where in blazes all that power 
went to. That's the answer. I'll bet I can tell  

640
01:04:01,600 --> 01:04:08,560
you right now what happened. We built that mercury 
up to a new level, and that transitional stage  

641
01:04:08,560 --> 01:04:14,080
was the red, crystalline metal. When it reached 
the higher stage, it was temporarily stable—but  

642
01:04:14,720 --> 01:04:18,880
that projector over there that we designed 
for the purpose of holding open electric  

643
01:04:18,880 --> 01:04:24,240
and magnetic fields just opened the door 
and let all that power right out again."

644
01:04:25,600 --> 01:04:28,240
"But why isn't it atomic energy?  

645
01:04:28,240 --> 01:04:32,640
How do you know that no more than your power 
that you put in is coming out?" demanded Devin.

646
01:04:33,920 --> 01:04:40,160
"The arc, man, the arc. That was a high-current, 
and low-voltage arc. Couldn't you tell by the  

647
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:46,800
sound that no great voltage—as atomic voltages 
go—was smashing across there? If we were getting  

648
01:04:46,800 --> 01:04:51,520
atomic voltage—and power—there'd have been 
a different tone to it, high and shriller.

649
01:04:52,880 --> 01:04:54,400
"Now, did you take any readings?"

650
01:04:55,120 --> 01:05:00,240
"What do you think, man? I'm human. Do you 
think I got any readings with that thing  

651
01:05:00,240 --> 01:05:05,440
bellowing and shrieking in my ears, and burning 
my skin with ultra-violet? It itches now."

652
01:05:07,040 --> 01:05:14,320
Kendall laughed. "You know what to do for an itch. 
Now, I'm going to make a bet. We had those points  

653
01:05:14,320 --> 01:05:20,640
separated for a half-million volts discharge, but 
there was a dust-cover thrown over them just now.  

654
01:05:21,440 --> 01:05:26,880
That, you notice, is missing. I'll bet that 
served as a starter lead for the main arc.  

655
01:05:27,600 --> 01:05:31,360
Now I'm going to start that projector 
thing again, and move the points  

656
01:05:31,360 --> 01:05:35,840
there through about six inches, and 
that thing probably won't start itself."

657
01:05:37,840 --> 01:05:40,560
Most of the laboratory staff 
had collected at the doorway,  

658
01:05:40,560 --> 01:05:46,080
looking in at the white-hot tungsten discharge 
points, and the now silent "atomic engine."  

659
01:05:46,960 --> 01:05:52,640
Kendall turned to them and said: "The 
flop picked itself up. You go on back,  

660
01:05:52,640 --> 01:05:57,360
we seem to be all in one piece yet. Douglass, 
you didn't get any readings, did you?"

661
01:05:58,960 --> 01:06:06,160
Sheepishly, Douglass grinned at him. "Eh—er—no—but 
I tore my pants. The magnetic field grabbed me and  

662
01:06:06,160 --> 01:06:12,640
I jumped. They had some steel buttons, and a lot 
of steel keys—they're kinda' hard to keep on now."

663
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:17,920
The laboratory staff broke into 
a roar of laughter, as Douglass,  

664
01:06:17,920 --> 01:06:20,880
holding up his trousers 
with both hands was beheld.

665
01:06:22,640 --> 01:06:24,640
"I guess the field worked," he said.

666
01:06:25,600 --> 01:06:32,320
"I guess maybe it did," adjudged Kendall 
solemnly. "We have some rope here if you need it—"

667
01:06:32,320 --> 01:06:33,920
Douglass returned to his post.

668
01:06:35,200 --> 01:06:38,800
Swiftly, Kendall altered the atomic 
distortion storage apparatus,  

669
01:06:38,800 --> 01:06:41,440
and returned to the power-board. "Ready?"

670
01:06:42,480 --> 01:06:42,720
"Check."

671
01:06:43,920 --> 01:06:50,720
Kendall shoved home the switch. The storage 
device was silent. Only a slight feeling of  

672
01:06:50,720 --> 01:06:56,240
strain made itself felt, and the sudden 
noisy hum of a small transformer nearby.  

673
01:06:57,440 --> 01:07:01,360
"She works, Buck!" Devin called. 
"The readings check almost exactly."

674
01:07:02,800 --> 01:07:07,440
"All good then. Now I want 
to get to that atomic thing.  

675
01:07:07,440 --> 01:07:10,640
We can let that slide for a 
little bit—I'll answer it."

676
01:07:11,360 --> 01:07:15,680
The telephone had rung noisily. 
"Kendall Labs—Kendall speaking."

677
01:07:17,040 --> 01:07:20,640
"This is Superintendent Foster, of 
the New York Power, Mr. Kendall.  

678
01:07:21,520 --> 01:07:26,080
We have some trouble just now that we think 
your operations may be responsible for.  

679
01:07:26,800 --> 01:07:31,520
The sub-station at North Beaumont blew all the 
fuses, and threw the breakers at the main station.  

680
01:07:32,160 --> 01:07:35,760
The men out there said the 
transformers began howling—"

681
01:07:35,760 --> 01:07:38,400
"Right you are—I'm afraid I did do that.  

682
01:07:39,200 --> 01:07:43,440
I had no idea that it would reach so 
far. How far is that from my place here?"

683
01:07:45,120 --> 01:07:48,160
"It's about a thousand yards, 
according to the survey maps."

684
01:07:49,200 --> 01:07:54,160
"Thanks—and I'll be careful about it. Any 
damage, I am responsible for? All okay?"

685
01:07:55,600 --> 01:07:56,880
"Yes, sir, Mr. Kendall."

686
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:02,400
Kendall hung up. "We stirred up a lot 
more dust than we expected, Devin.  

687
01:08:03,040 --> 01:08:07,440
Now let's start seeing if we can keep track 
of it. Douglass, how did your readings show?"

688
01:08:08,720 --> 01:08:12,480
"I took them at the ten stations, and here 
they are. The stations are two feet apart."

689
01:08:13,360 --> 01:08:31,760
"H-m-m—.5—.55—.6—.7—20—198—5950—6010—6012—5920. 
Very, very nice—only the darned thing's got  

690
01:08:31,760 --> 01:08:36,160
an arm as long as the law. Your 
readings were about .2, Devin?"

691
01:08:36,800 --> 01:08:38,000
"That's right."

692
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:42,240
"Then these little readings are just 
leakage. What's our normal intensity here?"

693
01:08:43,040 --> 01:08:47,520
"About .19. Just a very small 
fraction less than the readings."

694
01:08:48,800 --> 01:08:55,200
"Perfect—we have what amounts to a hollow 
shell of magnetic force—we can move inside,  

695
01:08:55,200 --> 01:09:00,800
and you can move outside—far enough. But you can't 
get a conductor or a magnetic field through it."  

696
01:09:01,840 --> 01:09:06,160
He put the readings on the bench, and 
looked at the apparatus across the room.  

697
01:09:06,160 --> 01:09:11,840
"Now I want to start right on that other. 
Douglass, you move that magnetostat apparatus  

698
01:09:11,840 --> 01:09:15,440
out of the way, and leave just the 
'can-opener' of ours—the projector.  

699
01:09:16,080 --> 01:09:21,760
I'm pretty sure that's what does the deed. 
Devin, see if you can hunt up some electrostatic  

700
01:09:21,760 --> 01:09:26,160
voltmeters with a range in the neighborhood 
of—I think it'll be about eighty thousand."

701
01:09:27,920 --> 01:09:32,160
Rapidly, Douglass was dismounting the 
apparatus, as Devin started for the stock room.  

702
01:09:33,120 --> 01:09:37,840
Kendall started making some new connections, 
reconnecting the apparatus they had intended  

703
01:09:37,840 --> 01:09:42,080
using on the "atomic engine," 
largely high-capacity resistances.  

704
01:09:43,120 --> 01:09:49,840
He seemed to perform this work mechanically, 
his mind definitely on something else. Suddenly  

705
01:09:49,840 --> 01:09:52,880
he stopped, and looked carefully 
into the receiver of the machine.  

706
01:09:53,920 --> 01:10:00,320
The metal in it was silvery, liquid, and here and 
there a floating crystal of the dull red metal.  

707
01:10:01,360 --> 01:10:05,520
Slowly a smile spread across 
his face. He turned to Douglass.

708
01:10:06,880 --> 01:10:12,080
"Douglass—ah, you're through. Get on the trail of 
MacBride, and get him and his crew to work making  

709
01:10:12,080 --> 01:10:17,600
half a dozen smaller things like this. Tell 
'em they can leave off the tungsten shield.  

710
01:10:17,600 --> 01:10:22,800
I want different metals in the receiver of each. 
Use—hmmm—sodium—copper—magnesium—aluminium,  

711
01:10:24,800 --> 01:10:26,480
iron and chromium. Got it?"

712
01:10:27,600 --> 01:10:33,280
"Yes, sir." He left, just as Devin returned 
with a large electrostatic voltmeter.

713
01:10:34,880 --> 01:10:40,240
"I'd like," said he, "to know how you know the 
voltage will range around eighty thousand."

714
01:10:42,160 --> 01:10:48,320
"K-ring excitation potential for mercury. I'm 
willing to bet that thing simply shoved the whole  

715
01:10:48,320 --> 01:10:54,400
electron system of the mercury out a notch—that 
it simply hasn't any K-ring of electrons now.  

716
01:10:55,200 --> 01:11:00,240
I'm trying some other metals. Douglass is going to 
have MacBride make up half a dozen more machines.  

717
01:11:00,960 --> 01:11:07,040
Machines—they need a name. 
This—ah—this is an 'atostor.'  

718
01:11:07,600 --> 01:11:12,720
MacBride's going to make up half a dozen of 
'em, and try half a dozen metals. I'm almost  

719
01:11:12,720 --> 01:11:18,640
certain that's not mercury in there now, at all. 
It's probably element 99 or something like it."

720
01:11:19,680 --> 01:11:20,960
"It looks like mercury—"

721
01:11:22,080 --> 01:11:29,040
"Certainly. So would 99. Following the periodic 
table, 99 would probably have an even lower  

722
01:11:29,040 --> 01:11:34,880
melting point than mercury, be silvery, dense 
and heavy—and perhaps slightly radioactive.  

723
01:11:35,680 --> 01:11:41,680
The series under the B family of Group II 
is Magnesium, Zinc, Cadmium, Mercury—and 99.  

724
01:11:42,560 --> 01:11:48,000
The melting point is going down all the 
way, and they're all silvery metals. I'm  

725
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:53,840
going to try copper, and I fully expect it 
to turn silvery—in fact, to become silver."

726
01:11:54,400 --> 01:11:59,600
"Then let's see." Swiftly they hooked up 
the apparatus, realigned the projector,  

727
01:11:59,600 --> 01:12:04,720
and again Kendall took his place at the 
power-board. As he closed the switch, on  

728
01:12:04,720 --> 01:12:11,600
no-load, the electrostatic voltmeter flopped over 
instantly, and steadied at just over 80,000 volts.

729
01:12:13,040 --> 01:12:17,120
"I hate to say 'I told you so,'" said 
Kendall. "But let's hook in a load.  

730
01:12:17,920 --> 01:12:22,000
Try it on about 100 amps first."

731
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:27,360
Devin began cutting in load. The resistors 
began heating up swiftly as more and more  

732
01:12:27,360 --> 01:12:33,280
current flowed through them. By not so much 
as by a vibration of the voltmeter needle,  

733
01:12:33,280 --> 01:12:43,440
did the apparatus betray any strain as the load 
mounted swiftly. 100—200—500—1000 amperes. Still,  

734
01:12:43,440 --> 01:12:49,680
that needle held steady. Finally, with a drain of 
ten thousand amperes, all the equipment available  

735
01:12:49,680 --> 01:12:55,600
could handle, the needle was steady as a rock, 
though the tremendous load of 800,000,000 watts  

736
01:12:55,600 --> 01:13:03,840
was cut in and out. That, to atoms, atoms by 
the nonillions, was no appreciable load at all.  

737
01:13:04,720 --> 01:13:12,320
There was no internal resistance whatever. The 
perfect accumulator had certainly been discovered.

738
01:13:13,200 --> 01:13:18,320
"I'll have to call McLaurin—" Kendall 
hurried away with a broad, broad smile.

739
01:13:37,360 --> 01:13:38,080
"Hello, Tom?"

740
01:13:39,120 --> 01:13:41,920
The telephone rattled in a peeved sort of way.  

741
01:13:42,960 --> 01:13:48,000
"Yes, it is. What now? And when am I going 
to see you in a social sort of way again?"

742
01:13:48,720 --> 01:13:55,200
"Not for a long, long time; I'm busy. I'm busy 
right now as a matter of fact. I'm calling up the  

743
01:13:55,200 --> 01:13:59,840
vice-president of Faragaut Interplanetary 
Lines, and I want to place an order."

744
01:14:00,560 --> 01:14:04,080
"Why bother me? We have clerks, 
you know, for that sort of thing,"  

745
01:14:04,080 --> 01:14:06,240
suggested Faragaut in a pained voice.

746
01:14:07,440 --> 01:14:09,680
"Tom, do you know how much I'm worth now?"

747
01:14:11,360 --> 01:14:16,400
"Not much," replied Faragaut promptly. "What 
of it? I hear, as a matter of fact that you're  

748
01:14:16,400 --> 01:14:21,200
worth even less in a business way. They're 
talking quite a lot down this way about an  

749
01:14:21,200 --> 01:14:26,480
alleged bank you're setting up on Luna. 
I hear it's got more protective devices,  

750
01:14:26,480 --> 01:14:32,400
and armor than any IP station in the System, 
that you even had it designed by an IP designer,  

751
01:14:32,400 --> 01:14:37,520
and have a gang of Colonels and Generals in 
charge. I also hear that you've succeeded in  

752
01:14:37,520 --> 01:14:42,240
getting rid of money at about one million 
dollars a day—just slightly shy of that."

753
01:14:43,120 --> 01:14:49,040
"You overestimate me, my friend. Much of 
that is merely contracted for. Actually  

754
01:14:49,040 --> 01:14:53,360
it'll take me nearly nine months to get 
rid of it. And by that time I'll have more.  

755
01:14:54,400 --> 01:14:57,840
Anyway, I think I have 
something like ten million left.  

756
01:14:58,560 --> 01:15:03,280
And remember that way back in the twentieth 
century some old fellow beat my record.  

757
01:15:03,280 --> 01:15:07,840
Armour, I think it was, lost a million 
dollars a day for a couple of months running.

758
01:15:09,520 --> 01:15:13,040
"Anyway, what I called you up 
for was to say I'd like to order  

759
01:15:13,040 --> 01:15:17,200
five hundred thousand tons of mercury, 
for delivery as soon as possible."

760
01:15:18,800 --> 01:15:25,280
"What! Oh, say, I thought you were going in for 
business." Faragaut gave a slight laugh of relief.

761
01:15:26,400 --> 01:15:35,840
"Tom, I am. I mean exactly what I say. I want 
five—hundred—thousand—tons of metallic mercury,  

762
01:15:35,840 --> 01:15:37,840
and just as soon as you can get it."

763
01:15:39,360 --> 01:15:41,440
"Man, there isn't that much in the system."

764
01:15:42,560 --> 01:15:47,760
"I know it. Get all there is on the market 
for me, and contract to take all the 'Jupiter  

765
01:15:47,760 --> 01:15:53,600
Heavy-Metals' can turn out. You send those orders 
through, and clean out the market completely.  

766
01:15:54,320 --> 01:15:57,360
Somebody's about to pay for the 
work I've been doing, and boy,  

767
01:15:57,360 --> 01:16:02,080
they're going to pay through the nose. After 
you've got that order launched, and don't make  

768
01:16:02,080 --> 01:16:07,280
a christening party of the launching either, 
why just drop out here, and I'll show you  

769
01:16:07,280 --> 01:16:12,800
why the value of mercury is going so high you 
won't be able to follow it in a space ship."

770
01:16:14,080 --> 01:16:20,480
"The cost of that," said Faragaut, seriously 
now, "will be about—fifty-three million at the  

771
01:16:20,480 --> 01:16:25,280
market price. You'd have to put up twenty-six 
cash, and I don't believe you've got it."

772
01:16:26,240 --> 01:16:30,000
Buck laughed. "Tom, loan me 
a dozen million, will you?  

773
01:16:30,720 --> 01:16:35,120
You send that order through, and then 
come see what I've got. I've got a break,  

774
01:16:35,120 --> 01:16:41,040
too! Mercury's the best metal for this 
use—and it'll stop gamma rays too!"

775
01:16:42,080 --> 01:16:45,200
"So it will—but for the love 
of the system, what of it?"

776
01:16:46,400 --> 01:16:49,760
"Come and see—tonight. Will 
you send that order through?"

777
01:16:51,120 --> 01:16:54,560
"I will, Buck. I hope you're 
right. Cash is tight now,  

778
01:16:54,560 --> 01:16:57,440
and I'll probably have to 
put up nearer twenty million,  

779
01:16:57,440 --> 01:17:01,840
when all that buying goes through. How long 
will it be tied up in that deal, do you think?"

780
01:17:03,520 --> 01:17:08,880
"Not over three weeks. And I'll guarantee you 
three hundred percent—if you'll stay in with  

781
01:17:08,880 --> 01:17:14,320
me after you start. Otherwise—I don't think 
making this money would be fair just now."

782
01:17:15,760 --> 01:17:19,360
"I'll be out to see you in about 
two hours, Buck. Where are you?  

783
01:17:19,360 --> 01:17:21,680
At the estate?" asked Faragaut seriously.

784
01:17:22,560 --> 01:17:24,640
"In my lab out there. Thanks, Tom."

785
01:17:26,240 --> 01:17:32,880
McLaurin was there when Tom Faragaut arrived. 
And General Logan, and Colonel Gerardhi. There  

786
01:17:32,880 --> 01:17:38,640
was a restrained air of gratefulness about all of 
them that Tom Faragaut couldn't quite understand.  

787
01:17:39,600 --> 01:17:44,400
He had been looking up Buck Kendall's famous 
bank, and more and more he had begun to wonder  

788
01:17:44,400 --> 01:17:51,040
just what was up. The list of stockholders had 
read like a list of IP heroes and executives.  

789
01:17:51,760 --> 01:17:58,000
The staff had been a list of IP men with a slender 
sprinkling of accountants. And the sixty-million  

790
01:17:58,000 --> 01:18:04,080
dollar structure was to be a bank without 
advertising of any sort! Usually such a venture  

791
01:18:04,080 --> 01:18:10,400
is planned and published months in advance. This 
had sprung up suddenly, with a strange quietness.

792
01:18:11,680 --> 01:18:15,200
Almost silently, Buck Kendall 
led the way to the laboratory.  

793
01:18:15,760 --> 01:18:20,800
A small metal tank was supported in a 
peculiar piece of apparatus, and from  

794
01:18:20,800 --> 01:18:28,880
it led a small platinum pipe to a domed apparatus 
made largely of insulum. A little pool of mercury,  

795
01:18:28,880 --> 01:18:35,120
with small red crystals floating in it rested in 
a shallow hollow surrounded by heavy conductors.

796
01:18:36,560 --> 01:18:42,880
"That's it, Tom. I wanted to show you first what 
we have, and why I wanted all that mercury. Within  

797
01:18:42,880 --> 01:18:49,600
three weeks, every man, woman and child in the 
system will be clamoring for mercury metal. That's  

798
01:18:49,600 --> 01:18:56,320
the perfect accumulator." Quickly he demonstrated 
the machine, charging it, and then discharging it.  

799
01:18:57,120 --> 01:19:04,560
It was better than 99.95% efficient on the 
charge, and was 100% efficient on the discharge.

800
01:19:05,600 --> 01:19:11,040
"Physically, any metal will do. Technically, 
mercury is best for a number of reasons.  

801
01:19:11,600 --> 01:19:16,160
It's a liquid. I can, and do it in 
this, charge a certain quantity,  

802
01:19:16,160 --> 01:19:20,720
and then move it up to the storage tank. 
Charge another pool, and move it up.  

803
01:19:21,440 --> 01:19:27,200
In discharge, I can let a stream flow in 
continuously if I required a steady, terrific  

804
01:19:27,200 --> 01:19:33,760
drain of power without interruption. If I wanted 
it for more normal service, I'd discharge a pool,  

805
01:19:33,760 --> 01:19:40,560
drain it, refill the receiver, and discharge a 
second pool. Thus, mercury is the metal to use.

806
01:19:41,440 --> 01:19:43,440
"Do you see why I wanted all that metal?"

807
01:19:44,880 --> 01:19:51,200
"I do, Buck—Lord, I do," gasped Faragaut. 
"That is the perfect power supply."

808
01:19:52,160 --> 01:19:59,200
"No, confound it, it isn't. It's a secondary 
source. It isn't primary. We're just as limited  

809
01:19:59,200 --> 01:20:05,360
in the supply of power as ever—only we have 
increased our distribution of power. Lord knows,  

810
01:20:05,360 --> 01:20:12,080
we're going to need a power supply badly enough 
before long—" Buck relapsed into moody silence.

811
01:20:13,280 --> 01:20:16,640
"What," asked Faragaut, looking 
around him, "does that mean?"

812
01:20:17,600 --> 01:20:23,040
It was McLaurin who told him of the stranger 
ship, and Kendall's interpretation of its meaning.  

813
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:29,200
Slowly Faragaut grasped the meaning behind 
Buck's strange actions of the past months.

814
01:20:31,120 --> 01:20:38,480
"The Lunar Bank," he said slowly, half to himself. 
"Staffed by trained IP men, experts in expert  

815
01:20:38,480 --> 01:20:44,000
destruction. Buck, you said something about the 
profits of this venture. What did you mean?"

816
01:20:45,200 --> 01:20:52,400
Buck smiled. "We're going to stick up IP to the 
extent necessary to pay for that fort—er—bank—on  

817
01:20:53,120 --> 01:20:57,280
Luna. We'll also boost the price 
so that we'll make enough to pay  

818
01:20:57,280 --> 01:21:00,560
for those ships I'm having made. 
The public will pay for that."

819
01:21:01,680 --> 01:21:05,680
"I see. And we aren't to stick the 
price too high, and just make money?"

820
01:21:06,480 --> 01:21:07,920
"That's the general idea."

821
01:21:09,440 --> 01:21:12,320
"The IP Appropriations Board 
won't give you what you need,  

822
01:21:12,320 --> 01:21:14,800
Commander, for real improvements on the IP ships?"

823
01:21:15,840 --> 01:21:18,320
"They won't believe Kendall. 
Therefore they won't."

824
01:21:19,360 --> 01:21:21,440
"What did you mean about gamma rays, Buck?"

825
01:21:22,240 --> 01:21:27,280
"Mercury will stop them and the Commander 
here intends to have the refitted ships built  

826
01:21:27,280 --> 01:21:33,120
so that the engine room and control room are one, 
and completely surrounded by the mercury tanks.  

827
01:21:33,680 --> 01:21:36,080
The men will be protected against the gamma rays."

828
01:21:37,600 --> 01:21:41,840
"Won't the rays affect the power stored 
in the mercury—perhaps release it?"

829
01:21:42,560 --> 01:21:47,280
"We tried it out, of course, and while 
we can't get the intensities we expect,  

830
01:21:47,280 --> 01:21:51,600
and can't really make any measurements of the 
gamma-ray energy impinging on the mercury—it  

831
01:21:52,160 --> 01:21:56,000
seems to absorb, and store that energy!"

832
01:21:56,000 --> 01:21:57,520
"What's next on the program, Buck?"

833
01:21:58,640 --> 01:22:03,280
"Finish those ships I have building. And 
I want to do some more development work.  

834
01:22:04,000 --> 01:22:07,600
The Stranger will return within 
six months now, I believe.  

835
01:22:08,320 --> 01:22:12,160
It will take all that time, and more 
for real refitting of the IP ships."

836
01:22:13,840 --> 01:22:19,040
"How about more forts—or banks, whichever 
you want to call them. Mars isn't protected."

837
01:22:19,920 --> 01:22:24,400
"Mars is abandoned," replied 
General Logan seriously. "We  

838
01:22:24,400 --> 01:22:27,760
haven't any too much to protect 
old Earth, and she must come first.  

839
01:22:28,560 --> 01:22:34,720
Mars will, of course, be protected as best 
the IP ships can. But—we're expecting defeat.  

840
01:22:35,920 --> 01:22:42,000
This isn't a case of glorious victory. It will 
be a case of hard won survival. We don't know  

841
01:22:42,000 --> 01:22:47,280
anything about the enemy—except that they are 
capable of interstellar flights, and have atomic  

842
01:22:47,280 --> 01:22:54,240
energy. They are evidently far ahead of us. Our 
battle is to survive till we learn how to conquer.  

843
01:22:55,040 --> 01:22:59,680
For a time, at least, the Strangers will have 
possession of most of the planets of the system.  

844
01:23:00,560 --> 01:23:06,000
We do not think they will be able to reach Earth, 
because Commander McLaurin here will withdraw his  

845
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:12,080
ships to Earth to protect the planet—and the great 
'Lunar Bank' will display its true character."

846
01:23:32,800 --> 01:23:36,240
Faragaut looked unsympathetically at Buck Kendall,  

847
01:23:36,240 --> 01:23:40,240
as he stood glaring perplexedly at 
the apparatus he had been working on.

848
01:23:41,680 --> 01:23:43,520
"What's the matter, Buck, won't she perk?"

849
01:23:44,560 --> 01:23:46,240
"No, damn it, and it should."

850
01:23:47,360 --> 01:23:52,560
"That," pointed out Faragaut, "is just 
what you think. Nature thinks otherwise.  

851
01:23:52,560 --> 01:23:57,760
We generally have to abide by her opinions. 
What is it—or what is it meant to be?"

852
01:23:58,960 --> 01:24:00,240
"Perfect reflector."

853
01:24:01,360 --> 01:24:04,160
"Make a nice mirror. What else, and how come?"

854
01:24:06,160 --> 01:24:11,040
"A mirror is just what I want. I 
want something that will reflect  

855
01:24:11,040 --> 01:24:17,280
all the radiation that falls on it. No metal 
will, even in its range of maximum reflectivity.  

856
01:24:18,000 --> 01:24:25,120
Aluminum goes pretty high, silver, on some ranges, 
a bit higher. But none of them reaches 99%.  

857
01:24:26,320 --> 01:24:30,320
I want a perfect reflector that I 
can put behind a source of wild,  

858
01:24:30,320 --> 01:24:34,720
radiant energy so I can focus it, and 
put it where it will do the most good."

859
01:24:36,320 --> 01:24:38,960
"Ninety-nine percent. Sounds pretty good.  

860
01:24:39,760 --> 01:24:43,920
That's better efficiency than most 
anything else we have, isn't it?"

861
01:24:43,920 --> 01:24:51,360
"No, it isn't. The accumulator is 100% efficient 
on the discharge, and a good transformer,  

862
01:24:51,360 --> 01:24:58,720
even before that, ran as high as 99.8 sometimes. 
They had to. If you have a transformer handling  

863
01:24:58,720 --> 01:25:04,880
1,000,000 horsepower, and it's even 1% 
inefficient, you have a heat loss of nearly  

864
01:25:04,880 --> 01:25:11,360
10,000 horsepower to handle. I want to use 
this as a destructive weapon, and if I hand  

865
01:25:11,360 --> 01:25:16,720
the other fellow energy in distressing amounts, 
it's even worse at my end, because no matter how  

866
01:25:16,720 --> 01:25:23,200
perfect a beam I work out, there will still be 
some spread. I can make it mighty tight though,  

867
01:25:23,200 --> 01:25:30,480
if I make my surface a perfect parabola. But 
if I send a million horse, I have to handle it,  

868
01:25:30,480 --> 01:25:34,640
and a ship can't stand several hundred 
thousand horsepower roaming around  

869
01:25:34,640 --> 01:25:40,240
loose as heat, let alone the weapon itself. 
The thing will be worse to me than to him.

870
01:25:41,200 --> 01:25:46,000
"I figured there was something worth investigating 
in those fields we developed on our magnetic  

871
01:25:46,000 --> 01:25:52,160
shield work. They had to do, you know, with 
light, and radiant energy. There must be some  

872
01:25:52,160 --> 01:25:58,080
reason why a metal reflects. Further, though 
we can't get down to the basic root of matter,  

873
01:25:58,080 --> 01:26:03,600
the atom, yet, we can play around just about as 
we please with molecules and molecular forces.  

874
01:26:04,560 --> 01:26:10,720
But it is molecular force that determines whether 
light and radiant energy of that caliber shall  

875
01:26:10,720 --> 01:26:18,160
be reflected or transmitted. Take aluminum as an 
example. In the metallic molecule state, the metal  

876
01:26:18,160 --> 01:26:26,000
will reflect pretty well. But volatilize it, and 
it becomes transparent. All gases are transparent,  

877
01:26:26,000 --> 01:26:32,320
all metals reflective. Then the secret of perfect 
reflection lies at a molecular level in the  

878
01:26:32,320 --> 01:26:39,520
organization of matter, and is within our reach. 
Well—this thing was supposed to make that piece  

879
01:26:39,520 --> 01:26:46,000
of silver reflective. I missed it that time." 
He sighed. "I suppose I'll have to try again."

880
01:26:47,920 --> 01:26:50,240
"I should think you'd use tungsten for that.  

881
01:26:51,040 --> 01:26:53,920
If you do have a slight leak, 
that would handle the heat."

882
01:26:55,040 --> 01:26:59,040
"No, it would hold it. Silver 
is a better conductor of heat.  

883
01:26:59,840 --> 01:27:01,760
But the darned thing won't work."

884
01:27:03,680 --> 01:27:08,240
"Your other scheme has." Faragaut laughed. 
"I came out principally for some signatures.  

885
01:27:08,960 --> 01:27:12,000
IP wants one hundred thousand tons of mercury.  

886
01:27:12,000 --> 01:27:15,680
I've sold most of mine already in 
the open market. You want to sell?"

887
01:27:16,800 --> 01:27:18,720
"Certainly. And I told you my price."

888
01:27:20,400 --> 01:27:27,040
"I know," sighed Faragaut. "It seems a shame 
though. Those IP board men would pay higher.  

889
01:27:27,040 --> 01:27:32,160
And they're so damn tight it seems a crime 
not to make 'em pay up when they have to."

890
01:27:33,200 --> 01:27:37,680
"The IP will need the money worse 
elsewhere. Where do I—oh, here?"

891
01:27:38,480 --> 01:27:41,760
"Right. I'll be out again this evening. 
The regular group will be here?"

892
01:27:42,560 --> 01:27:45,840
Kendall nodded as he signed in triplicate.

893
01:27:46,560 --> 01:27:50,080
That evening, Buck had found 
the trouble in his apparatus,  

894
01:27:50,080 --> 01:27:56,640
for as he well knew, the theory was right, only 
the practical apparatus needed changing. Before  

895
01:27:56,640 --> 01:28:02,160
the group composed of Faragaut, McLaurin and the 
members of Kendall's "bank," he demonstrated it.

896
01:28:04,000 --> 01:28:10,000
It was merely a small, model apparatus, with 
a mirror of space-strained silver that was an  

897
01:28:10,000 --> 01:28:16,480
absolutely perfect reflector. The mirror had been 
ground out of a block of silver one foot deep,  

898
01:28:16,480 --> 01:28:23,440
by four inches square, carefully annealed, and 
the work had all been done in a cooling bath. The  

899
01:28:23,440 --> 01:28:30,400
result was a mirror that was so nearly a perfect 
paraboloid that the beam held sharp and absolutely  

900
01:28:30,400 --> 01:28:36,560
tight for the half-mile range they tested it 
on. At the projector it was three and one-half  

901
01:28:36,560 --> 01:28:41,840
inches in diameter. At the target, it was three 
and fifty-two one hundredths inches in diameter.

902
01:28:43,600 --> 01:28:46,880
"Well, you've got the mirror, what 
are you going to reflect with it now?"  

903
01:28:46,880 --> 01:28:52,800
asked McLaurin. "The greatest problem is 
getting a radiant source, isn't it? You  

904
01:28:52,800 --> 01:28:57,360
can't get a temperature above about ten thousand 
degrees, and maintain it very long, can you?"

905
01:28:58,720 --> 01:29:00,880
"Why not?" Kendall smiled.

906
01:29:01,760 --> 01:29:04,400
"It'll volatilize and leave 
the scene of action, won't it?"

907
01:29:05,440 --> 01:29:08,000
"What if it's a gaseous source already?"

908
01:29:09,520 --> 01:29:16,560
"What? Just a gas-flame? That won't give you 
the point source you need. You're using just  

909
01:29:16,560 --> 01:29:23,120
a spotlight here, with a Moregan Point-light. That 
won't give you energy, and if you use a gas-flame,  

910
01:29:23,120 --> 01:29:28,080
the spread will be so great, that no matter how 
perfectly you figure your mirror, it won't beam."

911
01:29:29,360 --> 01:29:33,760
"The answer is easy. Not an ordinary gas-flame—a  

912
01:29:34,480 --> 01:29:41,120
very extra-special kind of gas-flame. Know 
anything about Renwright's ionization-work?"

913
01:29:41,920 --> 01:29:44,640
"Renwright—he's an IP man isn't he?"

914
01:29:45,680 --> 01:29:51,840
"Right. He's developed a system, which, thanks 
to the power we can get in that atostor,  

915
01:29:51,840 --> 01:29:56,720
will sextuply ionize oxygen 
gas. Now: what does that mean?"

916
01:29:58,240 --> 01:30:03,200
"Spirits of space! Concentrated 
essence of energy!"

917
01:30:04,080 --> 01:30:08,720
"Right. And in preparation, Cole 
here had one made up for me.  

918
01:30:09,440 --> 01:30:12,480
That—and something else. We'll just hook it up—"

919
01:30:13,760 --> 01:30:18,080
With Devin's aid, Kendall 
attached the second apparatus,  

920
01:30:18,080 --> 01:30:22,080
a larger device into which the silver 
block with its mirror surface fitted.  

921
01:30:22,880 --> 01:30:29,760
With the uttermost care, the two physicists lined 
it up. Two projectors pointed toward each other  

922
01:30:29,760 --> 01:30:34,880
at an angle, the base angles of a triangle, 
whose apex was the center of the mirror.  

923
01:30:35,840 --> 01:30:41,360
On very low power, a soft, glowing violet light 
filtered out through the opening of the one,  

924
01:30:41,360 --> 01:30:48,080
and a slight green light came from the other. 
But where the two streams met, an intense,  

925
01:30:48,080 --> 01:30:54,560
violet glare built up. The center of action was 
not at the focus, and slowly this was lined up,  

926
01:30:54,560 --> 01:31:00,240
till a sharp, violet beam of light reached 
out across the open yard to the target set up.

927
01:31:01,120 --> 01:31:05,040
Buck Kendall cut off the power, 
and slowly got into position.  

928
01:31:05,680 --> 01:31:13,120
"Now. Keep out from in front of that thing. Put on 
these glasses—and watch out." Heavy, thick-lensed  

929
01:31:13,120 --> 01:31:19,680
orange-brown goggles were passed out, and Kendall 
took his place. Before him, a thick window of  

930
01:31:19,680 --> 01:31:25,040
the same glass had been arranged, so that he 
might see uninterruptedly the controls at hand,  

931
01:31:25,600 --> 01:31:28,240
and yet watch unblinded, the action of the beam.

932
01:31:29,440 --> 01:31:36,000
Dully the mirror-force relay clicked. A hazy 
glow ran over the silver block, and died.  

933
01:31:37,120 --> 01:31:44,880
Then—simultaneously the power was thrown from two 
small, compact atostors into the twin projectors.  

934
01:31:45,520 --> 01:31:53,120
Instantly—a titanic eruption of light almost 
invisibly violet, spurted out in a solid, compact  

935
01:31:53,120 --> 01:32:00,160
stream. With a roar and crash, it battered its way 
through the thick air, and crashed into the heavy  

936
01:32:00,160 --> 01:32:05,920
target plate. A stream of flame and scintillating 
sparks erupted from the armor plate—and  

937
