01:50:49,200 --> 01:50:53,280
projected fields are oscillated, and they 
are tuned in with some parts of the ship.  

1120
01:50:53,840 --> 01:50:59,280
I suspect they are crystals of the metals. If 
they can start a vibration in the crystals of  

1121
01:50:59,280 --> 01:51:06,240
the metal—that's fatigue, metal fatigue enormously 
speeded. You know how a quartz crystal oscillator  

1122
01:51:06,240 --> 01:51:10,720
in a radio-control apparatus will break, if 
you work it on a very heavy load at the peak?  

1123
01:51:11,600 --> 01:51:17,120
They simply smash the crystals of metal in 
the same way. Only they project their field."

1124
01:51:18,560 --> 01:51:20,880
"Then our toughest metals are useless?  

1125
01:51:21,680 --> 01:51:28,080
Can't something tough, rather than hard, like 
copper or even silver for instance, stand it?"

1126
01:51:28,080 --> 01:51:32,880
"Calcium metal's the toughest going—and even that 
would break under the beating those ships give it.  

1127
01:51:33,680 --> 01:51:37,040
The only way to withstand it 
is to have such a mass of metal  

1128
01:51:37,040 --> 01:51:39,520
that the oscillations are damped out. But—"

1129
01:51:40,640 --> 01:51:46,800
The set tuned in on the IP station on Europa 
was speaking again. "The ships are returning.  

1130
01:51:46,800 --> 01:51:52,960
There are one hundred and twenty-nine by accurate 
count. Jorgsen reports that telescopic observation  

1131
01:51:52,960 --> 01:51:57,200
of the dead on the fallen cruiser show 
them to be a completely un-human race!  

1132
01:51:58,000 --> 01:52:03,440
They are of mottled coloring, predominately 
grayish brown. The ships are returning. They  

1133
01:52:03,440 --> 01:52:09,760
have divided into ten groups, nine groups of two 
each, and a main body of the rest of the fleet.  

1134
01:52:10,400 --> 01:52:15,840
The group of eighteen is descending within 
range, and we are focusing our beams on them—"

1135
01:52:16,560 --> 01:52:22,800
Out by Europa, ten great UV beams were stabbing 
angrily toward ten great interstellar ships.  

1136
01:52:23,840 --> 01:52:29,600
The metal of the hulls glowed brilliant, and 
distorted slowly as the thick walls softened  

1137
01:52:29,600 --> 01:52:36,640
under the heat, and the air behind pressed against 
it. Grimly the ten ships came on. Torpedoes were  

1138
01:52:36,640 --> 01:52:44,000
being launched, and exploded, and now they had 
no effect, for the Mirans within were protected.

1139
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:48,400
The eighteen grouped ships separated, and 
arranged themselves in a circle around the fort.  

1140
01:52:49,200 --> 01:52:54,000
Suddenly one staggered as a great puff of 
gas shot out through the thin atmosphere  

1141
01:52:54,000 --> 01:52:58,160
of Europa to flare brilliantly 
in the lash of the stabbing UV  

1142
01:52:58,160 --> 01:53:04,560
beam. Instantly the ship righted itself, and 
labored upward. Another dropped to take its place—

1143
01:53:05,840 --> 01:53:11,040
And the great walls of the IP fort suddenly 
groaned and started in their welded joints.  

1144
01:53:11,760 --> 01:53:16,400
The faint, whispering rustle of the crumbling 
beam was murmuring through the station.  

1145
01:53:17,280 --> 01:53:22,160
Engineers shouted suddenly as meters leapt the 
length of their scales, and the needles clicked  

1146
01:53:22,160 --> 01:53:28,720
softly on the stop pins. A thin rustle came from 
the atostors grouped in the great power room.  

1147
01:53:30,160 --> 01:53:34,160
"Spirits of Space—a revolving magnetic field!"  

1148
01:53:34,160 --> 01:53:39,840
roared the Chief Technician. "They're making 
this whole blasted station a squirrel cage!"

1149
01:53:41,040 --> 01:53:48,000
The mighty walls of eight-foot metal shuddered and 
trembled. The UV beams lashed out from the fort in  

1150
01:53:48,000 --> 01:53:53,440
quivering arcs now, they did not hold their aim 
steady, and the magnetic shield that protected  

1151
01:53:53,440 --> 01:54:00,240
them from atomic bombs was working and straining 
wildly. Eighteen great ships quivered and tugged  

1152
01:54:00,240 --> 01:54:06,640
outside there now, straining with all their power 
to remain in the same spot, as they passed on from  

1153
01:54:06,640 --> 01:54:13,040
one to another the magnetic impulses that were now 
creating a titanic magnetic vortex about the fort.

1154
01:54:14,800 --> 01:54:19,520
"The atostors will be exhausted in another 
fifteen minutes," the Chief Technician roared  

1155
01:54:19,520 --> 01:54:23,200
into his transmitter. "Can the signals 
get through those fields, Commander?"

1156
01:54:24,400 --> 01:54:26,000
"No, Mac. They've been stopped,  

1157
01:54:26,000 --> 01:54:30,640
Sparks tells me. We're here—and let's 
hope we stay. What's happening?"

1158
01:54:31,680 --> 01:54:35,840
"They've got a revolving magnetic field 
out there that would spin a minor planet.  

1159
01:54:36,720 --> 01:54:41,120
The whole blasted fort is acting like 
the squirrel cage in an induction motor!  

1160
01:54:41,760 --> 01:54:45,760
They've made us the armature in a five 
hundred million horsepower electric motor."

1161
01:54:46,880 --> 01:54:50,160
"They can't tear this place loose, can they?"

1162
01:54:50,160 --> 01:54:57,040
"I don't know—it was never—" The Chief stopped. 
Outside a terrific roar and crash had built up.  

1163
01:54:57,840 --> 01:55:01,440
White darts of flame leapt a 
thousand feet into the air,  

1164
01:55:01,440 --> 01:55:04,560
hurling terrific masses of 
shattered rock and soil.

1165
01:55:06,240 --> 01:55:11,760
"I was going to say," the Chief went on, "this 
place wasn't designed for that sort of a strain.  

1166
01:55:11,760 --> 01:55:14,320
Our own magnetic field is supporting us now,  

1167
01:55:14,320 --> 01:55:19,120
preventing their magnetic field from getting 
its teeth on metal. When the strain comes—well,  

1168
01:55:19,680 --> 01:55:22,320
they're cutting loose our 
foundation with atomic bombs!"

1169
01:55:23,520 --> 01:55:29,520
Five UV beams were combined on one interstellar 
ship. Instantly the great machine retreated,  

1170
01:55:29,520 --> 01:55:34,720
and another dropped in to take its place while 
the magnetic field spun on, uninterruptedly.

1171
01:55:35,920 --> 01:55:37,280
"Can they keep that up long?"

1172
01:55:38,400 --> 01:55:41,920
"God knows—but they have a 
hundred and more ships to send in  

1173
01:55:41,920 --> 01:55:43,920
when the power of one gives out, remember."

1174
01:55:44,960 --> 01:55:45,840
"What's our reserve now?"

1175
01:55:47,120 --> 01:55:51,840
The Chief paused a moment to look at the 
meters. "Half what it was ten minutes ago!"

1176
01:55:53,200 --> 01:55:59,520
Commander Wallace sent some other orders. Every 
torpedo tube of the station suddenly belched forth  

1177
01:55:59,520 --> 01:56:05,280
deadly, fifteen-foot torpedoes, most of 
them mud-torpedoes, torpedoes loaded with  

1178
01:56:05,280 --> 01:56:10,320
high explosive in the nose, a delayed fuse, 
and a load of soft clinging mud in the rear.  

1179
01:56:11,040 --> 01:56:15,920
The mud would flow down over the nose and 
offer a resistance foot-hold for the explosive  

1180
01:56:15,920 --> 01:56:21,680
which empty space would not. Four hundred and 
three torpedoes, equipped with anti-magnetic  

1181
01:56:21,680 --> 01:56:28,320
apparatus darted out. One hundred and 
four passed the struggling fields. One  

1182
01:56:28,320 --> 01:56:33,040
found lodgement on a Miran ship, and crushed 
in a metal wall, to be stopped by a bulkhead.

1183
01:56:34,000 --> 01:56:41,680
The Chief engineer watched his power declining. 
All ten UV beams were united in one now, driving  

1184
01:56:41,680 --> 01:56:48,080
a terrible sword of energy that made the attacked 
ship skip for safety instantly, yet the beams were  

1185
01:56:48,080 --> 01:56:53,680
all but useless. For the Miran reserves filled 
the gap, and the magnetic tornado continued.

1186
01:56:55,200 --> 01:57:01,840
For seventeen long minutes the station resisted 
the attack. Then the last of the strained mercury  

1187
01:57:01,840 --> 01:57:08,560
flowed into the receivers, and the vast power 
of the atostors was exhausted. Slowly the  

1188
01:57:08,560 --> 01:57:14,480
magnetic fields declined. The great walls of the 
station felt the clutching lines of force—they  

1189
01:57:14,480 --> 01:57:21,840
began to heat and to strain. A low, harsh grinding 
became audible over the roar of the atomic bombs.  

1190
01:57:22,720 --> 01:57:28,160
The whole structure trembled, and jumped 
slightly. The roar of bombs ceased suddenly,  

1191
01:57:28,160 --> 01:57:35,920
as the station jerked again, more violently. Then 
it turned a bit, rolled clumsily. Abruptly it  

1192
01:57:35,920 --> 01:57:42,000
began to spin violently, more and more rapidly. 
It started rolling clumsily across the plateau—

1193
01:57:43,680 --> 01:57:49,600
A rain of atomic bombs struck the unprotected 
metal, and the eighth breached the walls. The  

1194
01:57:49,600 --> 01:57:54,480
twentieth was the last. There was 
no longer an IP station on Europa.

1195
01:57:56,720 --> 01:58:01,360
"The difference," said Buck Kendall slowly, when 
the reports came in from scout-ships in space  

1196
01:58:01,360 --> 01:58:06,640
that had witnessed the last struggle, "between 
an atomic generator and an atomic power-store,  

1197
01:58:06,640 --> 01:58:11,440
or accumulator, is clearly shown. We 
haven't an adequate source of power."

1198
01:58:12,560 --> 01:58:16,960
McLaurin sighed slowly, and rose 
to his feet. "What can we do?"

1199
01:58:18,640 --> 01:58:23,200
"Thank our lucky stars that Faragaut here, and 
I, bought up all the mercury in the system,  

1200
01:58:23,200 --> 01:58:27,920
and had it brought to Earth. We at least 
have a supply of materials for the atostors."

1201
01:58:28,560 --> 01:58:29,920
"They don't seem to do much good."

1202
01:58:30,880 --> 01:58:33,760
"They're the best we've got. All the photocells on  

1203
01:58:33,760 --> 01:58:38,560
Earth and Venus and Mercury are at present 
busy storing the sun's power in atostors.  

1204
01:58:39,360 --> 01:58:43,280
I have two thousand tons of charged mercury 
in our tanks here in the 'Lunar Bank.'"

1205
01:58:44,480 --> 01:58:49,040
"Much good that will do—they can just 
pull and pull and pull till it's all gone.  

1206
01:58:49,920 --> 01:58:53,520
A starfish isn't strong, but he 
can open the strongest oyster  

1207
01:58:53,520 --> 01:58:58,160
just because he can pull from now 
on. You may have a lot of power—but."

1208
01:58:58,960 --> 01:59:06,480
"But—we also have those new fifteen-foot UV 
beams. And one fifteen-foot UV beam is worth,  

1209
01:59:06,480 --> 01:59:11,840
theoretically, nine five-foot beams, and 
practically, a dozen. We have a dozen of  

1210
01:59:11,840 --> 01:59:17,600
them. Remember, this place was designed not 
only to protect itself, but Earth, too."

1211
01:59:18,720 --> 01:59:20,240
"They can still pull, can't they?"

1212
01:59:21,040 --> 01:59:25,520
"They'll stop pulling when they get 
their fingers burned. In the meantime,  

1213
01:59:25,520 --> 01:59:29,840
why not use some of those IP ships to bring 
in a few more cargoes of charged mercury?"

1214
01:59:31,280 --> 01:59:32,560
"They aren't good for much else,  

1215
01:59:32,560 --> 01:59:35,760
are they? I wonder if those fellows 
have anything more we don't know?"

1216
01:59:37,440 --> 01:59:44,000
"Oh, probably. I'm going to work on that crumbler 
thing. That's the first consideration now."

1217
01:59:44,000 --> 01:59:44,240
"Why?"

1218
01:59:45,120 --> 01:59:49,760
"So we can move a ship. As it is, even 
those two we built aren't any good."

1219
01:59:50,880 --> 01:59:52,160
"Would they be anyway?"

1220
01:59:53,360 --> 01:59:57,040
"Well—I think I might disturb 
those gentlemen slightly.  

1221
01:59:57,040 --> 02:00:03,840
Remember, they each have a nose-beam eighteen 
feet across. Exceedingly unpleasant customers."

1222
02:00:05,680 --> 02:00:13,760
"Score: Strangers; magnetic field, atomic bombs, 
atomic power, crumbler ray. Home team; UV beams."

1223
02:00:14,560 --> 02:00:18,800
Kendall grinned. "I'd heard you were a 
pessimistic cuss when battle started—"

1224
02:00:19,680 --> 02:00:22,080
"Pessimistic, hell, I'm 
merely counting things up."

1225
02:00:23,600 --> 02:00:26,720
"McClellan had all the odds on 
Lee back in the Civil War of the  

1226
02:00:26,720 --> 02:00:29,280
States—but Lee sent him home faster than he came."

1227
02:00:30,320 --> 02:00:31,920
"But Lee lost in the end."

1228
02:00:32,480 --> 02:00:37,760
"Why bring that up? I've got work to do." 
Still smiling, Kendall went to the laboratory  

1229
02:00:37,760 --> 02:00:43,440
he had built up in the "Lunar Bank." Devin was 
already there, calculating. He looked unhappy.

1230
02:00:45,120 --> 02:00:49,760
"We can't do anything, as far as I can see. 
They're using an electric field all right,  

1231
02:00:49,760 --> 02:00:54,000
and projecting it. I can't 
see how we can do that."

1232
02:00:54,000 --> 02:01:00,400
"Neither can I," agreed Kendall, "so we can't use 
that weapon. I really didn't want to anyway. Like  

1233
02:01:00,400 --> 02:01:05,360
the neutron gun which I told Commander McLaurin 
would be useless as a weapon, they'd be prepared  

1234
02:01:05,360 --> 02:01:11,200
for it, you can be sure. All I want to do is 
fight it, and make their projection useless."

1235
02:01:12,080 --> 02:01:16,880
"Well, we have to know how they project it 
before we can break up the projection, don't we?"

1236
02:01:17,840 --> 02:01:22,160
"Not at all. They're using an 
electric field of very high frequency,  

1237
02:01:22,160 --> 02:01:29,440
but variable frequency. As far as I can see, all 
we need is a similar variable electric field of a  

1238
02:01:29,440 --> 02:01:33,760
slightly different frequency to heterodyne 
theirs into something quite harmless."

1239
02:01:34,720 --> 02:01:40,240
"Oh," said Devin. "We could, couldn't 
we? But how are you going to do that?"

1240
02:01:40,240 --> 02:01:41,680
"We'll have to learn, that's all."

1241
02:01:43,760 --> 02:01:50,400
Buck Kendall started trying to learn. In the 
meantime, the Mirans were taking over Jupiter.  

1242
02:01:51,600 --> 02:01:56,800
There were three IP stations on the planet itself, 
but they were vastly hindered by the thick,  

1243
02:01:56,800 --> 02:02:02,800
almost ultra-violet-proof atmosphere of Jupiter. 
Their rays were weak. And the magnetic fields of  

1244
02:02:02,800 --> 02:02:08,400
the Mirans were unaffected. Only their atomic 
bombs were hindered by the heavier gravity that  

1245
02:02:08,400 --> 02:02:11,840
pulled the rocks back in place faster 
than the bombs could throw them out.  

1246
02:02:12,880 --> 02:02:17,600
Still—a few hours of work, and the IP 
stations on Jupiter had rolled wildly  

1247
02:02:17,600 --> 02:02:22,000
across the flat plains of the planet like 
dented cans, to end in utter destruction.

1248
02:02:23,040 --> 02:02:26,720
The Mirans had paid no attention to the 
fleeing passenger and freighter ships  

1249
02:02:26,720 --> 02:02:32,160
that left the planet, loaded to the utmost 
with human cargo, and absolutely no freight.  

1250
02:02:32,160 --> 02:02:36,560
The IP fleet had to go to their rescue with 
oxygen tanks to take care of the extra humans,  

1251
02:02:37,120 --> 02:02:41,840
but nearly three-quarters of the population 
of Jupiter, a newly established population,  

1252
02:02:41,840 --> 02:02:47,200
and hence a readily mobile one, was saved. 
The others, the Mirans did not bother with  

1253
02:02:47,200 --> 02:02:50,880
particularly except when they happened to 
be near where the Mirans wanted to work.  

1254
02:02:51,520 --> 02:02:55,040
Then they were instantly destroyed 
by atomic bombing, or gamma rays.

1255
02:02:56,320 --> 02:03:00,480
The Mirans settled almost at once, and 
began their work of finding on Jupiter  

1256
02:03:00,480 --> 02:03:05,520
the badly needed atomic fuels. 
Machines were set up, and work begun,  

1257
02:03:05,520 --> 02:03:12,160
Mirans laboring under the gravity of the heavy 
planet. Then, fifty ships swam up again, reloaded  

1258
02:03:12,160 --> 02:03:16,960
with fuel, and with crews consisting solely 
of uninjured warriors, and started for Mars.

1259
02:03:18,400 --> 02:03:24,240
Mars was half way between her near conjunction and 
her maximum elongation with respect to Jupiter at  

1260
02:03:24,240 --> 02:03:30,480
that time. The Mirans knew their business though, 
for they started in on the IP station on Phobos.  

1261
02:03:31,280 --> 02:03:36,080
They were practiced by this time, and this 
IP station had only seven five-foot beams.  

1262
02:03:36,720 --> 02:03:42,560
In half an hour that station fell, and its sister 
station on Deimos followed. Three wounded ships  

1263
02:03:42,560 --> 02:03:48,240
returned to Jupiter, and ten new ships came 
out. The attack on Mars itself was started.

1264
02:03:49,840 --> 02:03:56,160
Mars was a different proposition. There were 
thirty-two IP stations here, one of them nearly  

1265
02:03:56,160 --> 02:04:02,720
as powerful as the Lunar Bank station. It was 
equipped with four of the huge fifteen-foot beams.  

1266
02:04:03,360 --> 02:04:06,960
And it had fifteen tons of 
mercury, more than seven-eighths  

1267
02:04:06,960 --> 02:04:13,520
charged. The Mars Center Station was located 
a short ten miles from the Mars Center City,  

1268
02:04:13,520 --> 02:04:18,160
and under the immediate orders of the IP 
heads, Mars Center City had been vacated.

1269
02:04:19,600 --> 02:04:25,360
For two days the Mirans hung off Mars, 
solidifying their positions on Phobos and Deimos.  

1270
02:04:26,320 --> 02:04:32,880
Then, with sixty-two ships, they attacked. They 
had made some very astute observations, and they  

1271
02:04:32,880 --> 02:04:38,720
started on the smaller stations just beyond the 
range of the Mars Center Station. Naturally,  

1272
02:04:38,720 --> 02:04:44,880
near so powerful a center, these stations had 
never been strong. They fell rapidly. But they  

1273
02:04:44,880 --> 02:04:50,720
had been counted on by Mars Center as auxiliary 
supports. McLaurin had sent very definite  

1274
02:04:50,720 --> 02:04:55,920
orders to Mars Center forbidding any action on 
their part, save gathering of power-supplies.

1275
02:04:57,280 --> 02:05:02,800
At last the direct attack on Mars Center was 
launched. For the first time, the Mirans saw  

1276
02:05:02,800 --> 02:05:09,840
one of the fifteen-foot beams. Mars' atmosphere is 
thin, and there is little ozone. The ultra-violet  

1277
02:05:09,840 --> 02:05:15,600
beams were nearly as effective as in empty space. 
When the Mirans dropped their ships, a full  

1278
02:05:15,600 --> 02:05:22,240
thirty of them, into the circle formation, Mars 
Center answered at once. All four beams started.

1279
02:05:23,920 --> 02:05:30,160
Those fifteen-foot beams, connected directly 
to huge atostor release apparatus, delivered a  

1280
02:05:30,160 --> 02:05:36,320
maximum power of two and three-quarter billion 
horsepower, each. The first Miran ship struck,  

1281
02:05:36,320 --> 02:05:42,080
sparkled magnificently, and a terrific cascade 
of white-hot metal rolled down from its nose.  

1282
02:05:42,720 --> 02:05:45,840
The great ship nosed down 
and to the left abruptly,  

1283
02:05:45,840 --> 02:05:51,120
accelerated swiftly—and crashed with tremendous 
energy on the plain outside of Mars Center City.  

1284
02:05:52,160 --> 02:05:57,680
White, unwavering flames licked up suddenly, 
and made a column five hundred feet high against  

1285
02:05:57,680 --> 02:06:03,360
the dark sky. Then the wreck exploded with a 
violence that left a crater half a mile across.

1286
02:06:04,560 --> 02:06:09,280
Three other ships had been struck, and were 
rapidly retreating. Another try was made  

1287
02:06:09,280 --> 02:06:15,280
for the ring formation, and four more ships were 
wounded, and replaced. The ring did not retreat,  

1288
02:06:15,280 --> 02:06:21,920
but the great magnetic field started. Atomic and 
gamma ray bombs started now, flashing sometimes  

1289
02:06:21,920 --> 02:06:27,520
dangerously close to the station as its magnetic 
field battled the rotating field of the ships.  

1290
02:06:28,560 --> 02:06:32,640
The four greater beams, and many smaller 
ones were in swift and angry action.  

1291
02:06:33,280 --> 02:06:38,880
Not more than a ten-second exposure could be 
endured by any one ship, before it must retreat.

1292
02:06:41,040 --> 02:06:48,000
For five minutes the Mirans hung doggedly at their 
task. Then, wisely, they retreated. Of the fleet,  

1293
02:06:48,000 --> 02:06:54,560
not more than seven ships remained untouched. 
Mars Center Station had held—at what cost  

1294
02:06:54,560 --> 02:07:00,480
only they knew. Five hundred tons of their mercury 
had been exhausted in that brief five minutes.  

1295
02:07:01,360 --> 02:07:05,440
One hundred tons a minute had flowed 
into and out of the atostor apparatus.  

1296
02:07:06,320 --> 02:07:08,880
Mars Center radioed for 
help, when the fleet lifted.

1297
02:07:10,000 --> 02:07:13,600
There was one other station on Mars 
that stood a good chance of survival,  

1298
02:07:14,800 --> 02:07:19,760
Deenmor Station, with three of the big beams 
installed, and apparatus for their fourth  

1299
02:07:19,760 --> 02:07:25,680
was in the station, and being rapidly worked 
over. McLaurin did a wise and courageous thing,  

1300
02:07:25,680 --> 02:07:33,040
at which every man on Mars cursed. He ordered 
that all IP stations save these two be deserted,  

1301
02:07:33,040 --> 02:07:37,200
and all mercury fuel reserves be 
moved to Deenmor and Mars Center.

1302
02:07:38,880 --> 02:07:43,760
The Mirans could not land on the North Western 
section of Mars, nor in the South Central region.  

1303
02:07:44,480 --> 02:07:50,080
Therefore Mars was not exactly habitable to 
Miran ships, because the great beams had been  

1304
02:07:50,080 --> 02:07:53,840
so perfectly figured that they were effective 
at a range of nearly twelve hundred miles.

