02:44:04,640 --> 02:44:10,800
of charged mercury remained in the tanks of 
Mars Center and 1950 in the tanks at Deenmor.

1666
02:44:11,920 --> 02:44:17,120
The flight of five ships settled comfortably 
upon Phobos, while the three relieved of duty  

1667
02:44:17,120 --> 02:44:23,599
started back to Jupiter. Immediately work 
was begun on the attack. The ships were  

1668
02:44:23,600 --> 02:44:28,640
first landed on the near side, while the 
apparatus of the projectors was unloaded,  

1669
02:44:29,279 --> 02:44:35,359
then the great ships moved around to the far 
side. Phobos of course rotated with one face  

1670
02:44:35,359 --> 02:44:40,719
fixed irrevocably toward Mars itself, 
the other always to the cold of space.  

1671
02:44:42,640 --> 02:44:48,480
Great power leads trailed beneath the ships, 
and to the dark side. Then there were huge  

1672
02:44:48,479 --> 02:44:54,479
water lines for cooling. On this almost weightless 
world, where the great ships weighing hundreds of  

1673
02:44:54,479 --> 02:45:00,000
thousands of tons on a planet, weighed so little 
they were frequently moved about by a single man,  

1674
02:45:00,000 --> 02:45:03,920
the laying of five miles of water 
conduit was no impossibility.

1675
02:45:04,960 --> 02:45:12,080
Then they were ready. Mars Center came 
first. Automatic devices kept the aim exact,  

1676
02:45:12,080 --> 02:45:17,840
as the first of the magnetic bombs 
started down. At five-second intervals  

1677
02:45:17,840 --> 02:45:24,240
they were projected outward, invisible globes 
of concentrated magnetic energy, undetectable  

1678
02:45:24,240 --> 02:45:30,719
in space. Seven seconds passed before the first 
became dimly visible in the thin air of Mars.  

1679
02:45:31,680 --> 02:45:38,480
It floated down, it would miss the fort it 
seemed—so far to one side— Abruptly it turned,  

1680
02:45:38,479 --> 02:45:43,519
and darted with tremendously accelerating 
speed for the great magnetic field of the fort.  

1681
02:45:44,399 --> 02:45:52,319
With a vast blast of light, it exploded. Five 
seconds later a second exploded. And a third.

1682
02:45:54,399 --> 02:45:58,799
Mars Center signaled scoffingly that the 
bombs were all being stopped dead in the  

1683
02:45:58,800 --> 02:46:03,520
magnetic atmosphere, after the bombardment 
had been witnessed from Earth and Luna.  

1684
02:46:04,319 --> 02:46:09,359
An hour later they gave a report that they were 
concentrated magnetic fields of energy that  

1685
02:46:09,359 --> 02:46:14,719
would be rather dangerous—if it weren't that they 
couldn't even stand into the magnetic atmosphere.  

1686
02:46:16,640 --> 02:46:22,161
Three hours later Mars Center reported that they 
contained considerably more energy than had at  

1687
02:46:22,160 --> 02:46:28,160
first been thought. Further, which they had not 
carefully considered at first, they were taking  

1688
02:46:28,160 --> 02:46:33,519
energy with them! They were taking away about 
an equal amount of energy as each blew up.

1689
02:46:34,640 --> 02:46:39,760
It was only a half-hour after that that the men 
at Mars Center realized perfectly what it meant.  

1690
02:46:40,640 --> 02:46:44,640
Their power was being drained just 
a little bit better than twice  

1691
02:46:44,640 --> 02:46:51,840
as fast as they generated during the day—and 
since Phobos spun so swiftly across the sky.

1692
02:46:52,640 --> 02:46:56,560
Deenmor got the attack just about 
the time Mars Center was released.  

1693
02:46:57,359 --> 02:47:03,359
Deenmor immediately began seeking for the 
source of it. Somewhere on Phobos—but where?

1694
02:47:05,120 --> 02:47:10,720
The Mirans were experts at camouflage. 
Deenmor Station, realizing the menace,  

1695
02:47:10,720 --> 02:47:16,560
immediately rayed the "projector." They tore up 
a great deal of harmless rock with their huge UV  

1696
02:47:16,560 --> 02:47:21,600
rays. But the bomb device continued 
to throw one bomb each five seconds.

1697
02:47:22,880 --> 02:47:28,720
When Deenmor operated from Phobos' position, Mars 
Center was exposed to the deadly, constant drain.  

1698
02:47:29,760 --> 02:47:33,840
A day or two later, the bombs were 
coming one each second and a half,  

1699
02:47:34,479 --> 02:47:36,879
for more ships had joined in the work on Phobos.

1700
02:47:38,479 --> 02:47:45,279
Gresth Gkae saw the work was going nicely. He knew 
that now it was only a question of time before  

1701
02:47:45,279 --> 02:47:53,439
those magnetic shields would fail—and then the 
whole fort would be powerless. Maybe—it might be  

1702
02:47:53,439 --> 02:47:59,200
a good idea, when the forts were powerless to 
investigate instead of blowing them up. There  

1703
02:47:59,200 --> 02:48:05,439
might be many interesting and worthwhile pieces 
of apparatus—particularly the UV beam's apparatus.

1704
02:48:21,279 --> 02:48:34,559
Buck Kendall entered the Communications room 
rather furtively. He hated the place. Cole was  

1705
02:48:34,560 --> 02:48:41,040
there, and McLaurin. Mac was looking tired and 
drawn, Cole not so tired, but equally drawn.  

1706
02:48:42,240 --> 02:48:46,800
The signals were coming through fairly well, 
because most of the disturbance was rising  

1707
02:48:46,800 --> 02:48:51,600
where the signals rose, and all the disturbance, 
practically, was magnetic rather than electric.

1708
02:48:53,600 --> 02:48:58,560
"Deenmor is sending, Buck," McLaurin said as he 
entered. "They're down to the last fifty-five  

1709
02:48:58,560 --> 02:49:05,760
tons. They'll have more time now—a rest while 
Phobos sinks. Mars Center has another 250 tons,  

1710
02:49:05,760 --> 02:49:09,760
but—it's just a question of time. 
Have you any hope to offer?"

1711
02:49:11,600 --> 02:49:18,080
"No," said Kendall in a strained voice. "But, Mac, 
I don't think men like those are afraid to die.  

1712
02:49:18,640 --> 02:49:25,920
It's dying uselessly they fear. Tell 'em—tell 
'em they've defended not alone Mars, but all  

1713
02:49:25,920 --> 02:49:31,600
the system, in holding up the Strangers on Mars. 
We here on Luna have been safer because of them.  

1714
02:49:32,399 --> 02:49:36,639
And tell—Mac, tell them that in the 
meantime, while they defended us,  

1715
02:49:36,640 --> 02:49:41,040
and gave us time to work, we have begun to 
see the trail that will lead to victory."

1716
02:49:42,319 --> 02:49:44,479
"You have!" gasped McLaurin.

1717
02:49:45,359 --> 02:49:52,240
"No—but they will never know!" Kendall left 
hastily. He went and stood moodily looking at the  

1718
02:49:52,240 --> 02:49:59,679
calculator machines—the calculator machines that 
refused to give the answers he sought. No matter  

1719
02:49:59,680 --> 02:50:06,000
how he might modify that original idea of his, no 
matter what different line of attack he might try  

1720
02:50:06,000 --> 02:50:12,240
in solving the problems of Space and Matter, while 
he used the system he knew was right—the answer  

1721
02:50:12,240 --> 02:50:17,359
came down to that deadly, hope-blasting 
expression that meant only "uncertain."

1722
02:50:18,800 --> 02:50:22,960
Even Buck was beginning to feel uncertain 
under that constant crushing of hope.  

1723
02:50:23,920 --> 02:50:29,359
Uncertainty—uncertainty was 
eating into him, and destroying—

1724
02:50:29,359 --> 02:50:32,399
From the Communications room 
came the hum and drive of the  

1725
02:50:32,399 --> 02:50:36,960
great sender flashing its message across 
seventy-two millions of miles of nothing.  

1726
02:50:38,319 --> 02:50:39,088
"B-u-c-k K-e-n-d-a-l-l s-a-y-s h-e 
h-a-s l-e-a-r-n-e-d s-o-m-e-t-h-i-n-g  

1727
02:50:39,089 --> 02:50:39,360
t-h-a-t w-i-l-l l-e-a-d t-o v-i-c-t-o-r-y 
w-h-i-l-e y-o-u h-e-l-d b-a-c-k t-h-e—"

1728
02:50:39,359 --> 02:50:56,639
Kendall switched on a noisy, 
humming fan viciously.  

1729
02:50:57,359 --> 02:51:00,559
The too-intelligible signals 
were drowned in its sound.

1730
02:51:01,359 --> 02:51:06,319
"And—tell them to—destroy the apparatus 
before the last of the power is gone,"  

1731
02:51:06,319 --> 02:51:07,920
McLaurin ordered softly.

1732
02:51:09,359 --> 02:51:15,920
The men in Deenmor station did slightly better 
than that. Gradually they cut down their magnetic  

1733
02:51:15,920 --> 02:51:21,279
shield, and some of the magnetic bombs tore 
and twisted viciously at the heavy metal walls.  

1734
02:51:22,240 --> 02:51:26,559
The thin atmosphere of Mars 
leaked in. Grimly the men waited.  

1735
02:51:27,359 --> 02:51:32,399
Atomic bombs—or ships to investigate? It 
did not matter much to them personally—

1736
02:51:34,160 --> 02:51:39,040
Gresth Gkae smiled with his old vigor as he 
ordered one of the great interstellar ships to  

1737
02:51:39,040 --> 02:51:44,399
land beside the powerless station, approaching 
from such an angle that the still-active Mars  

1738
02:51:44,399 --> 02:51:50,960
Center station could not attack. One of the fleet 
of Phobos rose, and circled about the planet, and  

1739
02:51:50,960 --> 02:51:57,520
settled gracefully beside the station. For half an 
hour it lay there quietly, waiting and watching.  

1740
02:51:58,720 --> 02:52:04,320
Then a crew of two dozen Mirans started 
across the dry, crumbly powder of Mars' sands,  

1741
02:52:04,319 --> 02:52:11,359
toward the fort. Simultaneously almost, 
three things happened. A three-foot UV  

1742
02:52:11,359 --> 02:52:17,599
beam wiped out the advancing party. A pair of 
fifteen-foot beams cut a great gaping hole in  

1743
02:52:17,600 --> 02:52:22,000
the wall of the interstellar ship, as 
it darted up, like a startled quail,  

1744
02:52:22,000 --> 02:52:25,680
its weapons roaring defiance, only 
to fall back, severely wounded.

1745
02:52:26,960 --> 02:52:31,920
And the radio messages pounded out to Earth 
the first description of the Miran people.  

1746
02:52:32,479 --> 02:52:38,000
Methodically the men in Deenmor station used 
all but one ton of their power to completely and  

1747
02:52:38,000 --> 02:52:43,520
forever wreck and destroy the interstellar cripple 
that floundered for a few moments on the sands  

1748
02:52:43,520 --> 02:52:51,440
a bare mile away. Presently, before Deenmor was 
through with it, the atomic bombs stopped coming,  

1749
02:52:51,439 --> 02:52:56,240
and the atomic shells. The magnetic 
shield that had been re-established  

1750
02:52:56,240 --> 02:52:59,439
for the few minutes of this 
last, dying sting, fell.

1751
02:53:00,560 --> 02:53:05,280
Deenmor station vanished in a sudden, 
colossal tongue of blue-green light  

1752
02:53:05,279 --> 02:53:11,759
as the ton of atomically distorted mercury was 
exploded by a projector beam turned on the tank.

1753
02:53:13,439 --> 02:53:17,679
It was long gone, when the first 
atomic bombs and magnetic bombs  

1754
02:53:17,680 --> 02:53:23,840
dropped from Phobos reached the spot, and 
only hot rock and broken metal remained.

1755
02:53:24,640 --> 02:53:30,960
Mars Center failed in fact the next time 
Phobos rode high over it. The apparatus here  

1756
02:53:30,960 --> 02:53:35,200
had been carefully destroyed by technicians 
with a view of making it indecipherable,  

1757
02:53:35,840 --> 02:53:41,279
but the Mirans made it even more certain, 
for no ship settled here to investigate,  

1758
02:53:41,279 --> 02:53:47,279
but a stream of atomic bombs that lasted for 
over an hour, and churned the rock to dust, and  

1759
02:53:47,279 --> 02:53:54,240
the dust to molten lava, in which pools of fused 
tungsten-beryllium alloy bubbled slowly and sank.

1760
02:53:56,080 --> 02:54:00,800
"Ah, Jarth—they are a brave race, 
whatever we may say of their queer shape,"  

1761
02:54:01,359 --> 02:54:06,240
sighed Gresth Gkae as the last of 
Mars Center sank in bubbling lava.  

1762
02:54:07,359 --> 02:54:12,240
"They stung as they died." For 
some minutes he was silent.

1763
02:54:14,720 --> 02:54:21,200
"We must move on," he said at length. "I have been 
thinking, and it seems best that a few ships land  

1764
02:54:21,200 --> 02:54:26,960
here, and establish a fort, while some twenty 
move on to the satellite of the third planet  

1765
02:54:26,960 --> 02:54:33,840
and destroy the fort there. We cannot operate 
against the planet while that hangs above us."

1766
02:54:34,560 --> 02:54:37,520
Seven ships settled to Mars, 
while the fleet came up from  

1767
02:54:37,520 --> 02:54:41,760
Jupiter to join with Gresth Gkae's 
flight of ships on its way to Luna.

1768
02:54:43,120 --> 02:54:48,880
An automatically controlled ship was sent ahead, 
and began the bombardment. It approached slowly,  

1769
02:54:48,880 --> 02:54:54,960
and was not destroyed by the UV beams till it 
had come to within 40,000 miles of the fort.  

1770
02:54:56,240 --> 02:55:03,040
At 60,000 Gresth Gkae stationed his 
fleet—and returned to 150,000 immediately  

1771
02:55:03,040 --> 02:55:08,240
as the titanic UV beams of the Lunar Fort 
stretched out to their maximum range.  

1772
02:55:09,520 --> 02:55:15,920
The focus made a difference. One ship started 
limping back to Jupiter, in tow of a second,  

1773
02:55:15,920 --> 02:55:21,279
while the rest began the slow, methodical work 
of wearing down the defenses of the Lunar Fort.

1774
02:55:22,319 --> 02:55:25,920
Kendall looked out at the 
magnificent display of clashing,  

1775
02:55:25,920 --> 02:55:30,880
warring energies, the great, whirling 
spheres and discs of opalescent flame,  

1776
02:55:31,439 --> 02:55:38,479
and turned away sadly. "The men at Deenmor must 
have watched that for days. And at Mars Center."

1777
02:55:39,840 --> 02:55:42,160
"How long can we hold out?" asked McLaurin.

1778
02:55:43,439 --> 02:55:49,599
"Three weeks or so, at the present rate. That's 
a long time, really. And we can escape if we  

1779
02:55:49,600 --> 02:55:55,201
want to. The UV beams here have a greater 
range than any weapon the Strangers have,  

1780
02:55:55,200 --> 02:55:59,439
and with Earth so near—oh, we 
could escape. Little good."

1781
02:56:00,640 --> 02:56:01,600
"What are you going to do?"

1782
02:56:03,120 --> 02:56:06,080
"I," said Buck Kendall, suddenly savage,  

1783
02:56:06,800 --> 02:56:12,719
"am going to consign all the math machines 
in the universe to eternal damnation—and  

1784
02:56:13,359 --> 02:56:19,439
go ahead and build a machine anyway. I know 
that thing ought to be right. The math's wrong."

1785
02:56:21,040 --> 02:56:22,640
"There is no other thing to try?"

1786
02:56:23,920 --> 02:56:29,520
"A billion others. I don't know how many 
others. We ought to get atomic energy somehow.  

1787
02:56:30,319 --> 02:56:35,599
But that thing infuriates me. A 
hundred things that math has predicted,  

1788
02:56:35,600 --> 02:56:41,121
that I have checked by experiment, simple 
little things. But—when I carry it through  

1789
02:56:41,120 --> 02:56:46,239
to the point where I can get something 
useful—it wriggles off into—uncertainty."

1790
02:56:48,000 --> 02:56:53,200
Kendall stalked off to the laboratory. Devin 
was there working over the calculus machines,  

1791
02:56:53,200 --> 02:56:59,279
and Kendall called him angrily. Then more 
apologetic, he explained it was anger at himself.  

1792
02:57:00,399 --> 02:57:06,080
"Devin, I'm going to make that thing, if it blows 
up and kills me. I'm going to make that thing if  

1793
02:57:06,080 --> 02:57:12,720
this whole fort blows up and kills me. That math 
has blown up in my face for four solid months,  

1794
02:57:12,720 --> 02:57:18,241
and half killed me, so I'm going to kill 
it. Come on, we'll make that damned junk."

1795
02:57:19,840 --> 02:57:26,000
Angrily, furiously, Kendall drove his helpers 
to the task. He had worked out the apparatus  

1796
02:57:26,000 --> 02:57:31,840
in plan a dozen times, and now he had the plans 
turned into patterns, the patterns into metal.

1797
02:57:33,359 --> 02:57:38,479
Saucily, the "S Doradus" made the trip to 
and from Earth with patterns, and with metal,  

1798
02:57:38,479 --> 02:57:43,200
with supplies and with apparatus. But 
she had to dodge and fight every inch  

1799
02:57:43,200 --> 02:57:46,240
of the way as the Miran ships 
swooped down angrily at her.  

1800
02:57:47,200 --> 02:57:52,240
A fighting craft could get through when the 
Miran fleet was withdrawn to some distance,  

1801
02:57:52,240 --> 02:57:57,120
but the Mirans were careful that no heavy-loaded 
freighter bearing power supply should get through.

1802
02:57:58,479 --> 02:58:05,040
And Gresth Gkae waited off Luna in his great ship, 
and watched the steady streams of magnetic bombs  

1803
02:58:05,040 --> 02:58:10,720
exploding on the magnetic shield of the 
Lunar Fort. Presently more ships came up,  

1804
02:58:10,720 --> 02:58:16,640
and added their power to the attack, for here, the 
photo-cell banks could gather tremendous energy,  

1805
02:58:16,640 --> 02:58:21,680
and Gresth Gkae knew he would need to overcome 
this, and drain the accumulated power.

1806
02:58:22,640 --> 02:58:26,880
Gresth Gkae felt certain if 
he could once crack this nut,  

1807
02:58:26,880 --> 02:58:32,800
break down Earth, he would have the system. 
This was the home planet. If this fell,  

1808
02:58:33,439 --> 02:58:38,479
then the two others would follow easily, despite 
the fact that the few forts on the innermost  

1809
02:58:38,479 --> 02:58:43,519
planet, Mercury, could gather energy from the sun 
at a rate greater than their ships could generate.

1810
02:58:45,120 --> 02:58:49,519
It took Kendall two weeks and three days 
to set up his preliminary apparatus.  

1811
02:58:50,240 --> 02:58:54,080
They had power for perhaps four 
days more, thanks to the fact that  

1812
02:58:54,080 --> 02:59:00,319
the long Lunar day had begun shortly after 
Gresth Gkae's impatient attack had started.  

1813
02:59:00,319 --> 02:59:06,080
Also, the "S Doradus" had brought in several 
hundred tons of charged mercury on each trip,  

1814
02:59:06,640 --> 02:59:12,161
though this was no great quantity individually, 
it had mounted up in the ten trips she had made.  

1815
02:59:13,040 --> 02:59:18,080
The "Cepheid," her sister ship, had gone along 
on seven of the trips, and added to the total.

1816
02:59:19,200 --> 02:59:23,920
But at length the apparatus was 
set up. It was peculiar looking,  

1817
02:59:23,920 --> 02:59:28,800
and it employed a great deal of power, 
nearly as much as a UV beam in fact.  

1818
02:59:29,760 --> 02:59:35,600
McLaurin looked at it sceptically toward the last, 
and asked Buck: "What do you expect it to do?"

1819
02:59:37,600 --> 02:59:44,241
"I am," said Kendall sourly, "uncertain. 
The result will be uncertainty itself."

1820
02:59:45,600 --> 02:59:50,000
Which, considering things, was a 
surprisingly accurate statement.  

1821
02:59:51,040 --> 02:59:57,680
Kendall gave the exact answer. He meant to 
give an ironic comment. For the mathematics  

1822
02:59:57,680 --> 03:00:02,241
had been perfectly correct, only Buck 
Kendall misinterpreted the answer.

1823
03:00:03,760 --> 03:00:08,080
"I've followed the math with mechanism 
all the way through," he explained,  

1824
03:00:08,080 --> 03:00:13,200
"and I'm putting power into it. That's all 
I know. Somewhere, by the laws of cause  

1825
03:00:13,200 --> 03:00:18,559
and effect, this power must show itself 
again—despite what the damn math says."

1826
03:00:20,000 --> 03:00:22,080
And in that, of course, Kendall was wrong.  

1827
03:00:22,800 --> 03:00:26,800
Because the laws of cause and effect 
didn't hold in what he was doing now.

1828
03:00:28,160 --> 03:00:31,519
"Do you want to watch?" he asked 
at length. "I'm all set to try it."

1829
03:00:32,479 --> 03:00:35,200
"I suppose I may as well." McLaurin smiled.  

1830
03:00:36,080 --> 03:00:39,680
"In our close-knit little community 
the fate of one is of interest to all.  

1831
03:00:40,399 --> 03:00:44,879
If it's going to blow up, I might as well 
be here, and if it isn't, I want to be."

1832
03:00:46,000 --> 03:00:51,840
Kendall smiled appreciatively and replied: 
"Let it be on thy own head. Here she goes."

1833
03:00:53,200 --> 03:00:58,000
He walked over to the power board, and 
took command. Devin, and a squad of other  

1834
03:00:58,000 --> 03:01:03,359
scientists were seated about the room with every 
conceivable type and combination of apparatus.  

1835
03:01:03,920 --> 03:01:10,160
Kendall wanted to see what this was doing. 
"Tubes," he called. "Circuits A and D. Tie-ins."  

1836
03:01:11,359 --> 03:01:18,160
He stopped, the preliminary switches in. 
"Main circuit coming." With a jerk he threw  

1837
03:01:18,160 --> 03:01:25,920
over the last contact. A heavy relay thudded 
solidly. The hum of a straining atostor. Then—

1838
03:01:28,000 --> 03:01:31,200
An electric motor, humming 
smoothly stopped with a jerk.  

1839
03:01:33,359 --> 03:01:40,240
"This," it remarked in a deep throaty voice, 
"is probably the last stand of humanity."

1840
03:01:42,240 --> 03:01:45,599
The galvanometer before which 
Devin was seated apparently agreed.  

1841
03:01:46,319 --> 03:01:48,960
In a rather high pitched 
voice it pointed out that:  

1842
03:01:49,760 --> 03:01:56,800
"If the Lunar Fort falls, the Earth—" It stopped 
abruptly, and an electroscope beside Douglass  

1843
03:01:56,800 --> 03:02:02,720
took up the thread in a high, shrill voice, 
rather slurred, "—will be directly attacked."

1844
03:02:03,680 --> 03:02:09,840
"This," resumed the motor in a hoarse voice, 
"will certainly mean the end of humanity."  

